{"title_page": "A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010 film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Nightmare on Elm Street\n| image          = A Nightmare on Elm Street 2010 poster.jpg\n| alt            = Movie poster of a man with a hat, looking down; the man's skin and clothes are heavily burnt; one bladed finger shows through clasped hands\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Samuel Bayer]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Bay]]\n* [[Andrew Form]]\n* [[Bradley Fuller|Brad Fuller]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Wesley Strick]]\n* [[Eric Heisserer]]\n}}\n| story          = Wesley Strick\n| based on       = {{basedon|Characters|[[Wes Craven]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jackie Earle Haley]]\n* [[Kyle Gallner]]\n* [[Rooney Mara]]\n* [[Katie Cassidy]]\n* [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]]\n* [[Kellan Lutz]]<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Steve Jablonsky]]\n| cinematography = Jeff Cutter\n| editing        = [[Glen Scantlebury]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Platinum Dunes]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[New Line Cinema]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|04|27|[[Hollywood]]|ref1=<ref>{{cite web|author=Hollywood.com Staff |url=http://www.hollywood.com/photos/misc/6844969/a-nightmare-on-elm-street-world-premiere#218272/0 |title=\"A Nightmare On Elm Street\" World Premiere |website=Hollywood.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-28}}</ref>|2010|04|30|United States|2010|05|7|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $35 million<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| gross          = $115.6 million<ref>{{cite web|title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=August 1, 2011| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110624060958/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm| archive-date= June 24, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>  <!--NOTE: Please update the figures at the bottom of the page in the Box Office section, as well as the Accessdate in the Citation Template. Thank you.-->\n}}\n\n'''''A Nightmare on Elm Street''''' is a 2010 American [[slasher film]] directed by [[Samuel Bayer]], and written by [[Wesley Strick]] and [[Eric Heisserer]]. The film stars [[Jackie Earle Haley]], [[Kyle Gallner]], [[Rooney Mara]], [[Katie Cassidy]], [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]], and [[Kellan Lutz]]. It is a [[remake]] of [[Wes Craven]]'s [[A Nightmare on Elm Street|1984 film of the same name]]. Produced by [[Michael Bay]] and [[Platinum Dunes]], the film was designed to reboot the [[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|''Nightmare on Elm Street'' franchise]] and is the ninth installment in the series. The film is set in a [[Fictional location|fictitious town]] of Ohio and centers around a group of teenagers living on one street who are stalked and murdered in their dreams by a disfigured man named [[Freddy Krueger]]. The teenagers discover that they all share a common link from their childhood that makes them targets for Krueger.\n\n''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was originally to follow the same design as Platinum Dunes' other remake, ''[[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|Friday the 13th]]'', where the writers took the best elements from each of the films in the original series and created a single storyline with them. Eventually, they decided to use Craven's original storyline but tried to create a scarier film. To that end, they decided to remove the one-line quipping Freddy, who had become less scary and more comical over the years, and bring back his darker nature. The writers developed the character to be a child molester, something that Craven wanted to do originally in 1984 but changed to a child killer instead. Freddy's physical appearance was changed with the use of computer-generated imagery to be closer to that of a burn victim. Because of the positive experiences Platinum Dunes' producers had in the area, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was filmed primarily in Illinois. Craven expressed his displeasure when he was not consulted on the project. [[Robert Englund]], who portrayed Freddy in the previous eight films, voiced his support of the remake and the casting of Haley in the role of Freddy.\n\n''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' had its world premiere at Hollywood on April 27, 2010, and was theatrically released in North America on April 30, 2010, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] and [[New Line Cinema]]. The film received generally negative reviews from critics, who criticized the teenage characters and story while offering some praise for Bayer's direction and Haley's performance. Despite this, it was box-office success, earned over $63 million at the domestic box office and over $115 million worldwide, making it the highest-grossing film in the franchise and the highest-grossing slasher film in unadjusted dollars.\n\n==Plot==\n<!--STOP. Wikipedia is not a substitute for watching a movie, and plot summaries should not contain every minor detail. They are here to SUMMARIZE the basic events. For a horror movie, we don't need to explain how every single character was killed, and what everyone is doing that isn't relevant to the overall plot. Thank you. !-->\n[[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Kris Fowles|Kris Fowles]] meets her friend, Dean Russell, at the Springwood Diner. Dean falls asleep at the table and dreams that he meets a severely burned man in seared clothes who has a bladed gardener's glove on his right hand. The man cuts Dean's throat in the dream, but it appears to Kris and their classmate, waitress [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Nancy Holbrook|Nancy Holbrook]], that Dean cuts himself. At Dean's funeral, Kris sees a photograph of her and Dean as children, but cannot recall knowing Dean before high school. Kris begins to dream about the burned man, then refuses to go to sleep for fear that she will die like Dean. Jesse Braun, Kris's ex-boyfriend, shows up to keep her company while she sleeps, but Kris meets the burned man in her dreams and is murdered. Covered in Kris's blood, Jesse runs to Nancy's house and learns that Nancy has been having nightmares about the same man\u2014[[Freddy Krueger|Freddy]]. Jesse tells Nancy that they need to stop Freddy and warns her not to fall asleep, then runs off.\n\nJesse is arrested by the police under suspicion of murdering Kris. He tries not to fall asleep in his jail cell but fails, and is killed by Freddy. As her friends die, Nancy questions everyone's connection to each other, given that none of them can remember each other before their teenage years. Nancy and her friend Quentin Smith discover that all of them attended Badham Preschool. Nancy's mother, Gwen, reluctantly tells Nancy and Quentin that there was a groundskeeper at the preschool, Fred Krueger, who was accused of [[child sexual abuse|sexually abusing]] the children. Gwen explains that Nancy was his favorite, and that she came home one day and told her mother about the things Krueger did to her in a secret room. Gwen alerted the other parents, including Quentin's father Alan, and Kris's mother Nora, but she tells the teenagers that Krueger escaped before he was arrested. Nancy does not believe her and attempts to track down the remaining kids from the school. She discovers that all of the other kids have been killed, most of them in their sleep, and after Jesse's death, only she and Quentin are left.\n\nQuentin tries to accept that his nightmares are nothing more than repressed memories, but he falls asleep during swim practice and witnesses what really happened to Krueger\u2014the parents tracked him down and burned him alive. Quentin and Nancy believe that Krueger, now a [[vengeful ghost]], wants revenge on them for lying as children. As a result of their [[insomnia]], they have sporadic [[microsleep]] episodes and become [[hypnagogia|hypnagogic]]. To try to stop Krueger, they decide to go to the preschool to learn what they can. On the way, Nancy is attacked by Krueger after a microsleep episode, but she pulls a piece of Krueger's sweater out of the dream world into reality. Quentin takes Nancy to the hospital where he steals [[epinephrine|adrenaline]] to help them stay awake. Finally at the preschool, they uncover Krueger's hidden room and the evidence that proves he did indeed abuse all of the children; they then realize that Kreuger wants revenge on them for telling the truth.\n\nNancy decides to pull Krueger out of the dream world and kill him in the real world. Quentin tries to stay awake long enough to pull Nancy out of her dream when she grabs Krueger, but he falls asleep and is attacked. Krueger goes after Nancy and explains that he deliberately left her for last so she would stay awake long enough to become comatose. Quentin awakens and uses the adrenaline to wake Nancy, who then pulls Krueger into reality. They fight and Nancy uses a broken paper cutter blade to kill him before she torches the secret room with Krueger's body inside. Nancy and Quentin escape. However, Krueger's remains are not found by the fire fighters who put out the fire. After Nancy and her mother return home from the hospital, Krueger suddenly appears.  While Nancy screams, Krueger kills Nancy's mother before pulling her body through a mirror and then disappearing.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Main|List of cast members of the Nightmare on Elm Street series|List of A Nightmare on Elm Street characters}}\n{{div col begin}}\n* [[Jackie Earle Haley]] as [[Freddy Krueger|Fred \"Freddy\" Krueger]]\n* [[Kyle Gallner]] as Quentin Smith\n* [[Rooney Mara]] as [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Nancy Holbrook|Nancy Holbrook]]\n**Kyra Krumins as young Nancy\n* [[Katie Cassidy]] as [[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Kris Fowles|Kris Fowles]]\n**Julianna Damm as young Kris\n* [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]] as Jesse Braun\n**Bayden Coyer as young Jesse\n* [[Kellan Lutz]] as Dean Russell\n**Max Holt as young Dean\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as Alan Smith \n* [[Connie Britton]] as Dr. Gwen Holbrook\n* Lia Mortensen as Nora Fowles\n* [[Kurt Naebig]] as Mr. Russell\n* Jennifer Robers as Mrs. Russell\n* [[Christian Stolte]] as Mr. Braun\n* [[Aaron Yoo]] as Marcus Yeon (uncredited) \n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn January 29, 2008, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Michael Bay]] and his [[Platinum Dunes]] production company would reboot the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' franchise with a remake of [[A Nightmare on Elm Street|the original 1984 film]].<ref name=\"NightAnno\">{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Michael|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979807.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=New Line sets up new 'Nightmare'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=January 29, 2008|accessdate=January 29, 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120529175832/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979807?refCatId=13|archive-date=May 29, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Producer Brad Fuller explained that they would follow the same tactic from their [[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|''Friday the 13th'' remake<!--STOP. Form and Fuller have consistently referred to the film as a \"remake\"!-->]]<nowiki/> and would abandon the things that had made the series less scary\u2014the film's antagonist, [[Freddy Krueger]], would not be \"cracking jokes\" as had become a staple of his character . The focus would be to \"make a horrifying movie\". Fuller said that the film would be a remake of the 1984 film, but clarified that they would borrow character deaths and dream sequences from the entire series.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=8835|title=Nightmare on Elm Street is Go, Shooting in Spring|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=December 11, 2008|accessdate=June 20, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212163646/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=8835|archive-date=December 12, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' announced that [[Samuel Bayer]] was hired to direct the film.<ref name=\"Director\">{{cite news|url=http://riskybusiness.hollywoodreporter.com/2009/02/11/a-director-moves-onto-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |last=Zeitchik |first=Steven |title=A director moves onto (Nightmare on) Elm Street |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]] |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=February 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517041553/http://riskybusiness.hollywoodreporter.com/2009/02/11/a-director-moves-onto-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |archive-date=May 17, 2010 }}</ref> According to New Line production chief Toby Emmerich, Michael Bay advocated heavily for Bayer because he had \"the ability to capture the kind of seductive and unsettling imagery that would make ''Nightmare'' feel like a fresh, visually arresting moviegoing experience.\"<ref name=\"LAint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-bigpicture14-2009jul14,0,698071.story|title='Nightmare on Elm Street' returns|last=Goldstein|first=Patrick|date=July 14, 2009|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> Bayer declined Platinum Dunes' offer twice but finally accepted after Bay emailed him and explained the kind of business opportunity it would be.<ref name=\"Bayerint\">{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=14330|title=1:1 With Nightmare on Elm Street's Sam Bayer|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=CraveOnline|date=March 2, 2010|accessdate=March 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306114246/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=14330|archive-date=March 6, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 95%; background:#F0F8FF; color:black; width:30em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"It's definitely not a standard slasher film. This is a movie that you can mention to people and their jaws drop ... because of that franchise, that character, had a profound effect on their childhood. ... I hear things like, 'Freddy scared the hell out of me.' ... What everyone involved wants to do is re-invent the character for a new generation.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014 Samuel Bayer on remaking ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''.<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n|}\nIn a June 9, 2009 interview, Craven, who directed the original movie and was not consulted for the remake, expressed displeasure with the new film.<ref name=\"Cravenint\">{{cite news|last=Parfitt|first=Orlando|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/992/992845p1.html|title=Craven's Elm Street Nightmare Exclusive: Original director angry over remake.|work=[[IGN Entertainment]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=June 9, 2009|accessdate=June 19, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612044359/http://movies.ign.com/articles/992/992845p1.html|archive-date=June 12, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> In contrast, [[Robert Englund]], who portrayed Freddy throughout the film series, felt it was time for ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' to be remade. Englund liked the idea of being able to \"exploit the dreamscape\" with computer-generated imagery and other technologies that did not exist when Craven made the original in 1984.<ref name=\"Englundint\">{{cite news|last=McCabe|first=Joseph|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b15904_exclusive_robert_englund_on_jackie.html|title=Robert Englund on Jackie Earle Haley and the 'Nightmare' Remake!|work=[[FEARnet]]|publisher=Horror Entertainment|date=June 27, 2009|accessdate=June 29, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701121100/http://www.fearnet.com/news/b15904_exclusive_robert_englund_on_jackie.html|archive-date=July 1, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Bayer believes that his film paid homage to what Craven did in 1984, but did not replicate it entirely. Bayer recognized that Craven attempted to put more meaning into his films and that the character of Freddy Krueger affected the lives of a generation of people. For Bayer, remaking ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was about bringing that feeling to a new generation with a new spin on the character and story.<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n\nFuller and Form likened the new film to their [[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (2003 film)|2003 remake of ''The Texas Chain Saw Massacre'']] but instead of a remake, they saw it as more of a reimagining.<ref name=\"setpreview\">{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11115|title=Set Visit Preview: A Nightmare on Elm Street|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=CraveOnline|date=July 21, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090723081206/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11115|archive-date=July 23, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The pair also explained that ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' would have a different tone than their ''Friday the 13th'' remake. Form states, \"I think a ''Friday the 13th'' movie like we made was really fun. You know, sex, drugs and rock and roll, and I think a Nightmare movie is not that.\"<ref name=\"SiFi\">{{cite news|url=http://scifiwire.com/2009/07/join-us-behind-the-scenes.php|title=UPDATED: Behind the scenes of the new Nightmare on Elm Street|last=Gilchrist|first=Todd|date=July 22, 2009|work=[[Sci-Fi Wire]]|publisher=[[SyFy]]|accessdate=July 30, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104221257/http://blastr.com/2009/07/join-us-behind-the-scenes.php|archive-date=January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked why New Line was rebooting the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' film series, Emmerich explained, \"The Nightmare films are profoundly disturbing on a deep, human level because they're about our dreams. It's why we thought that we could reach an especially broad audience with a new film, since the feeling of having your dreams being invaded was something that would translate to any country and any culture.\"<ref name=\"LAint\"/> Overall, Bayer wanted to create a film in \"a darker world\" that made the audience ask, \"What makes a monster?\"\u2014is it a monster because of its physical appearance, someone with a scarred face and a clawed glove, or is it a monster because of something deeper within the man himself.<ref name=\"Rotint\"/>\n\n===Writing===\nWesley Strick was initially hired to pen a script for a new ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' because he had impressed Emmerich with a prequel script he wrote for the 1995 film ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Seven]]''. Eric Heisserer was subsequently hired to provide a rewrite of Strick's script before the film moved into production.<ref name=\"LAint\"/> When Bayer came on board he received a script that reflected the combined efforts of Strick and Heisserer and which still \"needed to be tinkered with\". Bayer explained that the script goes deeper into \"[Freddy] as a person [and] how he became the thing he was\". Bayer expressed that unlike the ''Friday the 13th'' remake that picked the best parts from the first four films, the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' remake was coming straight from the first film.<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n\nFor the remake, Freddy was brought back to his darker roots and away from the comical character he had become in later ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' sequels. Fuller pointed out that this Freddy did have one-liners but they come from a darker sense of humor and were not intended to be as campy as in previous films. Craven's original characterization of Freddy as a [[Child sexual abuse|child molester]] was used because if Freddy killed children, as in the original, it would have been easy for the teenage characters to figure out using the Internet what had happened.<ref name=\"Bloodint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19996|title=Producer Brad Fuller Talks 'A Nightmare on Elm Street'|author=Chris Eggertsen|date=April 28, 2010|work=Bloody Disgusting|accessdate=April 29, 2010|publisher=The Collective}}</ref> In an effort to keep the story fresh, Heisserer developed the concept of micro-naps because the dream-reality sequences could become repetitive. The micro-nap allowed them to \"blur reality and the dream world, and get some great scares\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19219|title=Set Visit: A Trip to 'A Nightmare on Elm Street' Part One|work=Bloody Disgusting|publisher=The Collective|date=February 22, 2010|accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n{{Wide image|A Nightmare on Elm Street panel at WonderCon 2010 1.JPG|450px|The cast at [[WonderCon]] 2010. From left to right: Dekker, Cassidy, Mara, Gallner, and Haley.|box width|right|alt=Five actors from the cast, sitting at a long table, each with a microphone. The backdrop has the WonderCon logo. The actors from left to right are Dekker, Cassidy, Mara, Gallner, and Haley.}}\nIn February 2009, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' revealed Robert Englund would not reprise the role of Freddy Krueger for the remake; Englund had performed the role for the eight previous films.<ref name=\"Director\"/> On April 3, 2009 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' reported that [[Jackie Earle Haley]] was cast to take over Englund's most well-known role.<ref name=\"Haleyanno\">{{cite news|last=Rich|first=Joshua|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/nightmare-haley.html|title='Nightmare on Elm Street' reboot: Jackie Earle Haley to play Freddy Krueger|work=Hollywood Insider|date=April 3, 2009|accessdate=April 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405090144/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/nightmare-haley.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 5, 2009}}</ref> Initially, the studio wanted to cast an unknown for the role of Freddy Krueger, but it was Haley's performance in ''[[Little Children (film)|Little Children]]'' that impressed Emmerich enough to cast the actor against the original intentions. Emmerich explained, \"Freddy is this incredible stew of malevolence and anger, but he also has a hint of vulnerability, and Jackie really has all of that and more. He just seemed completely right for the part.\"<ref name=\"LAint\"/> Bayer stated that he and producers Form and Fuller managed to acquire the screen test Haley gave as [[Rorschach (comics)|Rorschach]] for ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]''; after viewing it, Bayer said it \"blew [his] mind\", and that he knew Haley would be able to go deep and create a believable character who was a psychopath \"with a burned face and a claw.\"<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n\nHaley said the first time he heard his name mentioned in conjunction with the character was from people on the Internet who suggested he be cast. Later he learned that his agents were already in talks with Brad Fuller.<ref name=\"MTVint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1625034/nightmare-on-elm-street-new-freddy-krueger-thanks-fans-for-casting/|title='Nightmare On Elm Street' New Freddy Krueger Thanks Fans For Casting|last=Carroll|first=Larry|date=October 31, 2009|work=MTV|accessdate=April 29, 2010|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]}}</ref> Haley stated that he was apprehensive about taking on the role of a character with such a dark past\u2014that of a child murderer\u2014for about a \"minute and a half\". Knowing the Freddy Krueger in the remake would be even darker, Haley came quickly to the realization that he was doing a horror film and this was just a fictional character. Haley said that once he embraced the idea of Freddy as a \"mythical boogeyman\", it became \"very freeing\" for him as an actor.<ref name=\"Rotint\">{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=15025|title=Video Interviews: A Nightmare on Elm Street|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=CraveOnline|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=April 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504051934/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=15025|archive-date=May 4, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 95%; background:#F0F8FF; color:black; width:28em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"Jackie is not big, and I think that Jackie's size is gonna really work ... one of the metaphors ... I've used for Freddy is a little rabid dog that just bites your ankle and holds on ... and I think Jackie brings that, with his own physicality, to the role, without ever having to work it a little bit.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014 Robert Englund on Jackie Earle Haley as Freddy Krueger.<ref name=\"Englundint\"/>\n|}\nHaley is contracted for three films which includes the remake and two sequels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jackie Earle Haley Signed on for Three ''Elm Street'' Films!|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16621|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=July 1, 2009|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> Englund stated he agreed with the casting of Haley and that he feels Haley's physical size works in this role.<ref name=\"Englundint\"/> Haley stated that he did not intend to have Englund's original performances influence his own and that he used the frustration of having to sit in the make-up chair for three-and-a-half hours as his motivation to get into character.<ref name=\"setpreview\"/>\n\n[[Rooney Mara]] plays the role of Nancy Holbrook;<ref name=\"theindependent\">{{cite news |title= Classic horror film 'A Nightmare On Elm Street' gets updated|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/classic-horror-film-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-gets-updated-1956347.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=April 28, 2010|accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref> Mara is also contracted for a sequel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rooney Mara Signed on For ''Elm Street'' Sequel|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16566|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=June 24, 2009|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> Bayer describes Nancy as \"the loneliest girl in the world\".<ref name=\"prodnote\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nightmareonelmstreet.com/media/downloads/NOES_ProdNotes.pdf|title=Production Notes from ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''|publisher=Official Nightmare on Elm Street website|format=PDF|accessdate=April 24, 2010}}</ref> Mara stated that her Nancy is different than the role of [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy Thompson]], performed by Heather Langenkamp, and described her character as \"socially awkward and timid and really doesn't know how to connect with people\".<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> [[Kyle Gallner]] was cast as Quentin, who forms a connection with Nancy. Gallner described his character as \"a mess, more jittery and more 'out there' than Nancy is\".<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Gallner pointed out that his character is like this because of the amount of pharmaceuticals he ingests to stay awake. Producer Brad Fuller commented that Gallner brought a sense of \"humanity and relatability\" to the role with his compassion and intellect.<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Other cast members include [[Katie Cassidy]], [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]], and [[Kellan Lutz]]. Cassidy performed the role of Kris. According to Cassidy, Kris becomes an emotional wreck throughout the film. Cassidy described her character's ordeal: \"She is literally dragged through hell, having to crawl through dark, claustrophobic tunnels. She's always crying and freaking out as her nightmares of Freddy bleed into her everyday life. Kris suspects there's something that connects her with the others; she even confronts her mother about it, but no one's talking.\"<ref name=\"prodnote\"/>\n\nDekker portrays Jesse, Kris's ex-boyfriend. According to Dekker, \"Jesse kind of knows what's going on but refuses to believe it.\"<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Dekker explained that Jesse spends so much time trying to convince himself that Freddy is not real, that by the time he does meet Freddy face-to-face, \"he's just a mess. ... There's no bravado about it. His terror is very real.\"<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Lutz plays Dean, Kris's current boyfriend and \"a well-liked, well-off high school jock.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Vary |first=Adam |title=''Twilight'' star Kellan Lutz in final talks to join ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' |url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/24/kellan-lutz-elm/ |work=Hollywood Insider |date=April 23, 2009 |accessdate=May 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010144152/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/24/kellan-lutz-elm/ |archive-date=October 10, 2009 }}</ref> [[Connie Britton]], [[Clancy Brown]] and [[Elvis Jasso Mar\u00edn]] also star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/NEFCOFHFXdTdJN|title=First Look at Freddy Krueger and the New Poster for A Nightmare on Elm Street|date=July 22, 2009|work=Movie Web|publisher=[[Comcast|Comcast Digital]]|accessdate=May 5, 2010}}</ref> Gallner and Mara explained that the teenagers in the remake are \"a little more aware\" of Freddy and their situation, whereas in the original Nancy and her friends were \"more mellow\" and \"nonchalant\"  until they were finally killed.<ref name=\"Rotint\"/>\n\n===Krueger's design===\n[[File:Freddy Krueger (Jackie Earle Haley).jpg|thumb|Haley wore prosthetic appliances on his face that were blended together to appear seamless and designed to look close to an actual burn victim. [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] was used on portions of his face\u2014like his cheek\u2014that appear open.|alt=A picture of the face of a man with severe burns. Parts of skin are burned through and appear hollow. The head has a hit and the glove with finger knives is in the forefront. ]]\nForm and Fuller explained that Freddy's physical appearance would more accurately resemble a burn victim.<ref name=\"SiFi\"/> Form later clarified that there was a fine line they did not want to cross when it came to making Freddy look like a burn victim. According to the producer, the crew had many reference photos of burn victims which detailed how white the skin would appear after healing. Form did not want the audience to turn away in disgust every time Freddy was on the screen, so they opted to hold back on some of the realism. Fuller noted how horrific the images were and how difficult they were to look at.<ref name=\"Shockset\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=14163|title=Set Visit: A Nightmare Reborn on Elm Street|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|date=February 22, 2010|work=Shock Till You Drop|accessdate=May 2, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313183639/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=14163|archive-date=February 2, 2013|url-status=dead|publisher=CraveOnline}}</ref> The special effects crew that worked on ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' and created the computer-generated images (CGI) for [[Two-Face]], were brought in to work on the CGI for Freddy's face. The CGI is used in conjunction with the special effects make-up that Haley wears.<ref name=\"Rotint\"/> The prosthetic appliances used to create Freddy's physical look were designed by Andrew Clement. Haley described the experience of wearing the prosthetic devices and make-up as \"pretty encumbering\".<ref name=\"fearint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b18350_Jackie_Earle_Haley_Talks_Playing_Freddy_Krueger.html|title=Jackie Earle Haley Talks Playing Freddy Krueger|work=FEARnet|publisher=Horror Entertainment|last=Raffel|first=Lawrence P.|date=March 3, 2010|accessdate=April 29, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120405123611/http://www.fearnet.com/news/b18350_Jackie_Earle_Haley_Talks_Playing_Freddy_Krueger.html|archive-date=April 5, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhen production started, Clement and his crew would spend six hours applying Haley's make-up; eventually, the crew was able to streamline the process.<ref name=\"Shockset\"/> According to Haley, the make-up crew would glue individual prosthetic devices from his head all the way down his back. The appliances were then blended together to create a seamless appearance. Haley spent approximately three hours and twenty minutes each day in the make-up chair to apply the appliances; on occasion, it would take almost four-and-a-half hours when the crew also needed to apply the prosthetic skull cap. Haley did not need to worry about the skull cap most days because he was able to wear the fedora on top of his head. Haley also had to wear contact lenses\u2014one bloody, one cloudy. The cloudy contact lens made it difficult for the actor to see.<ref name=\"fearint\"/> Haley also had to work on developing Freddy's voice for the film. According to Haley, the process of coming up with the perfect voice for Freddy was \"this organic process of embodying the character\", and not about just \"sitting around the table and going, 'Let me try this voice and this voice{{'\"}}. Haley and Bayer admitted that some of the voice would be digitally enhanced to give it a \"supernatural quality\" and differentiate it from the voice Haley used as [[Rorschach (comics)|Rorschach]] in ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]''.<ref name=\"SDCC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=11247|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|title=SDCC Press Conference: A Nightmare on Elm Street|publisher=Crave Online Media|work=Shock Till You Drop|date=July 30, 2009|accessdate=April 30, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008181750/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=11247|archive-date=October 8, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Budding Film Industry in Gary, Indiana.jpg|thumb|left|Filming at former City Methodist Church in [[Gary, Indiana]].|alt=Six lights on a rig lighting up and in front of a Gothic Revival style church building.]]\nWith a budget of $35 million,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/04/nightmare-to-rule-at-home-while-iron-man-explodes-overseas.html|title=Movie projector: 'Nightmare' to rule at home with $30 million while 'Iron Man 2' explodes to $100 million-plus overseas|last= Fritz|first=Ben|date=April 29, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=April 30, 2010|quote=The new \"Nightmare\" isn't expected to do quite that well but should still be a solid performer for the studio given its production budget of about $35 million.}}</ref> [[principal photography]] began on May 5, 2009, and officially [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] on July 10, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.qconline.com/archives/qco/display.php?id=436859|title=2 Chicago-area schools to be horror movie sites|publisher=Quad Cities Online|agency=Associated Press|date=April 27, 2009|accessdate=April 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11047|title=That's a Wrap on Nightmare on Elm Street|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=[[Bradley Fuller|Brad Fuller]]|date=July 10, 2009|accessdate=July 10, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090712071815/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11047|archive-date=July 12, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Because of the positive experiences Platinum Dunes' producers had in the area when producing ''The Amityville Horror'' and ''The Unborn'', they chose to film in Illinois. Platinum Dunes also received a thirty percent tax break for filming in the state. The producers looked for locations that were \"old and decaying\" to mirror the look of Krueger. They settled on the Ryerson Steel warehouse on the west side of Chicago to film most of the scenes in which the townspeople burn Krueger alive.<ref name=\"10quest\">{{cite news|last=Arroyave|first=Luis|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/chi-091030-nightmare-elm-questions-pictures,0,6957467.photogallery|title=10 questions about new 'Nightmare on Elm Street' answered|work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103095524/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/chi-091030-nightmare-elm-questions-pictures,0,6957467.photogallery|archive-date=November 3, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nNew Line contracted with two high schools in Illinois, [[Elk Grove High School (Elk Grove Village, Illinois)|Elk Grove High School]] and [[John Hersey High School]], to shoot scenes for the remake. According to Nancy Holman, principal of Elk Grove High, the studio contacted schools across the nation looking for one that had a swimming pool. Although filming took place at both schools, neither was identified by name. The studio cast 200 extras for various school scenes, including one in the pool, but required that all students who auditioned be at least 16 years old.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zalusky|first=Steve|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/story/?id=289286|title=Freddie's coming to Elk Grove, Hersey high schools|work=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]|publisher=Paddock Publications|date=April 27, 2009|accessdate=May 6, 2009}}</ref> Lenore Gonzales Bragaw, school board president, was initially apprehensive about the deal as she disliked the idea of the studio filming \"scenes of violence\" at the schools; Bragaw agreed once she was assured that no one would be killed during the pool scenes.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Graydon Megan |author2= John Keilman|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-talk-nightmare-follomay01,0,7725616.story|title=Chicago school district won't look a gift 'Nightmare' in the mouth|work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Company|date=May 1, 2009|accessdate=May 7, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504135854/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-talk-nightmare-follomay01,0,7725616.story|archive-date=May 4, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 22, 2009, the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' film crew went on location to the city of [[Gary, Indiana]] to film scenes at a Methodist church. The studio had negotiated with the city for months before finally settling on a deal. According to Ben Clement, the executive director of the Gary Office of Film and Television, the studio was looking for \"an architectural style that would fit the story line of the film\". The film crew returned to the streets of Gary first in June to film a dream sequence that takes place on Elm Street and later in December to shoot some scenes in a diner.<ref>{{cite news|author=Staff|url=http://www.thetimesonline.com/articles/2009/05/21/updates/breaking_news/doc4a158020018cd165290762.txt|title=Gary set to be backdrop for scenes in Freddy Krueger remake|work=The Times |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=May 21, 2009|accessdate=June 20, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/105/1053106p1.html|title=Freddy's Nightmare Continues: Casting call notice online for additional Elm Street filming|last=Vejvoda|first=Jim|work=[[IGN Entertainment]]|publisher=News Corporation|date=December 8, 2009|accessdate=December 28, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120710061447/http://movies.ign.com/articles/105/1053106p1.html|archive-date=July 10, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Fuller and Form, Warner Bros. suggested ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' be released in [[3D film|3D]] because of the increased box office revenue of recent 3D films. It was the opinion of the Platinum Dunes producers that if a film was not initially conceived as 3D, then it should not be converted to 3D; Fuller and Form fought the studio to keep the remake 2D. Warner Bros. and Platinum Dunes came to agree that a 3D movie would not be \"the best version of the movie\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Weintraub|first=Steve|url=http://www.collider.com/2010/04/26/exclusive-interview-producers-andrew-form-and-brad-fuller-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-plus-updates-on-monster-squad-ouija-friday-the-13th-2-and-the-nightmare-blu-ray-will-have-a-6-minute-alternat/|title=Exclusive Interview: Platinum Dunes Producers Andrew Form and Brad Fuller ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''|website=Collider|date=April 26, 2010|accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe score to ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was composed by [[Steve Jablonsky]]<!-- http://www.hans-zimmer.com/index.php?rub=disco&id=926 --> and recorded by a 60-piece string ensemble of the [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]].<ref name=scoring>{{cite news|last=Goldwasser|first=Dan|url=http://www.scoringsessions.com/news/216/|title=Steve Jablonsky scores ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''|publisher=ScoringSessions.com|date=March 26, 2010|accessdate=March 26, 2010}}</ref> The movie soundtrack was released by [[WaterTower Music]] on April 27, 2010.<ref name=WaterTower>{{cite news|title=WaterTower Music to Release \"A Nightmare on Elm Street\" Feature Film Soundtrack on April 27, 2010|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/04/22/idUS225641+22-Apr-2010+BW20100422|accessdate=June 24, 2014|work=Reuters|publisher=Business Wire|date=April 22, 2010|location=Burbank, California|quote=\"A Nightmare on Elm Street\" is being distributed worldwide by Warner Bros. Pictures, a Warner Bros. Entertainment Company.}}</ref> [[Charles Bernstein (composer)|Charles Bernstein]]'s original ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' theme and \"Jump Rope\" rhyme, The Hit Crew's \"Un Homme Et Une Femme\", and [[The Everly Brothers]]' \"[[All I Have to Do Is Dream]]\" are heard in the film but only Bernstein's \"Jump Rope\" rhyme is included in the soundtrack.\n\n==Release==\n''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was released on April 30, 2010, to 3,332 theaters and approximately 4,700 screens,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2746&p=.htm|title=Weekend Briefing: 'Nightmare on Elm Street,' 'Furry Vengeance'|author=Brandon Gray|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|work=Box Office Mojo|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100501225750/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2746&p=.htm| archive-date= May 1, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> making it the twelfth-widest opening for an R-rated film in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/widestmpaa.htm?page=R&p=.htm|title=Widest Openings By MPAA Rating|publisher=Internet Movie Database|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=April 29, 2010}}</ref> Comparatively, the original ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was only released to 165 theaters at its opening on November 9, 1984 and by the end of its box office run its widest release was 380 theaters.<ref name=\"OrigNight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=elmst.htm|title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984) Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=April 29, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100501225248/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=elmst.htm| archive-date= May 1, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The 2010 remake holds the record for widest ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' release, beating out ''[[Freddy vs. Jason]]'' by 318 theaters.<ref name=\"Nightcomp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=nightmareonelmstreet.htm|title=Nightmare on Elm Street Filmography Comparison|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=April 29, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100504181150/http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=nightmareonelmstreet.htm| archive-date= May 4, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on October 5, 2010. The DVD's only feature is a featurette, \"Freddy Krueger Reborn\". The Blu-ray special features include the DVD's featurette along with a deleted scene, an alternate opening and ending, and the Maniacle Movie Mode.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dvdactive.com/news/releases/a-nightmare-on-elm-street4.html | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (US \u2013 DVD R1  BD) in News \u2013 Releases at DVDActive | publisher=DVDActive | date=July 23, 2010 | accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nIn March 2010, the [[National Entertainment Collectibles Association]] (NECA) released two new Freddy Krueger action figures; one pre-burned Freddy with Jackie Earle Haley's likeness, and one based on the new burn design from the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' remake.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36392/necas-new-freddy-figure-all-fired-up|title=NECA's New Freddy Figure All Fired Up|work=DreadCentral.com|publisher=CraveOnline|date=March 13, 2010|accessdate=March 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826165157/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36392/necas-new-freddy-figure-all-fired-up|archive-date=August 26, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> NECA also released a replica of Freddy's clawed glove.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36548/neca-gives-us-a-better-look-freddys-glove-from-a-nightmare-elm-street-2010|title=NECA Gives Us a Better Look at Freddy's Glove From A Nightmare on Elm Street 2010|work=DreadCentral.com|publisher=CraveOnline|date=March 23, 2010|accessdate=March 23, 2010}}</ref> An online game was released in conjunction with the film\u2014the player attempts to keep a young girl awake using coffee, cold showers, self-mutilation, and other means, to keep her safe from Freddy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19482|title=Keep Her Awake in New 'Elm Street' Online Game|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=Bloody Disgusting|publisher=The Collective|date=March 16, 2010|accessdate=March 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nEarly estimates put ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''{{'}}s opening-day gross at approximately $15 million with a projected opening weekend of $35 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/01/box-office-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |last=Sperling |first=Nicole |title=Box office: Friday numbers put Freddy Krueger in top spot with a $15 million night |publisher=CNN |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=May 1, 2010 |accessdate=May 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503004518/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/01/box-office-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |archive-date=May 3, 2010 }}</ref> Included in the $15 million was the $1.6 million the film made from midnight showings on Thursday night from 1,000 theaters. As a result, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' broke the record for midnight openings for a horror film that was previously held by the ''[[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' remake in 2009 that grossed $1 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/05/freddys-a-dream-nightmare-on-elm-street-sets-record-for-horror-midnights-15m-17m-today-and-40m-weekend-predictions/|last=Finke|first=Nikki|title=Freddy's A (Rotten) Dream: 'Nightmare On Elm Street Opens To $15.8M Friday, $35M Weekend; 'Furry Vengeance' Bombs|publisher=Mail.com Media Corporation|work=Deadline.com|date=May 1, 2010|accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> Ultimately, the film finished its opening with $32,902,299, placing first for the weekend ahead of ''[[How to Train Your Dragon (film)|How to Train Your Dragon]]'' (6th week in release), ''[[Date Night]]'' (4th week in release), ''[[The Back-up Plan]]'' (2nd week in release), and ''[[Furry Vengeance]]'' (1st week in release).<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=18&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office: April 30 \u2013 May 2, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=May 2, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100505173625/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=18&p=.htm| archive-date= May 5, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' dropped 72 percent in its second weekend, earning $9,119,389. It dropped to second place behind the newly released ''[[Iron Man 2]]''.<ref name=\"weekend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm|title=Weekend Grosses|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 11, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100513064015/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm| archive-date= May 13, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The film dropped an additional 54 percent in its third week, bringing in $1.5 million, though it remained in the top 10 rankings for the weekend, placing sixth overall.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brandon Gray|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2776&p=.htm|title=Friday Report: 'Iron Man 2' Fends Off 'Robin Hood'|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|date=May 15, 2010|accessdate=May 16, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100520010951/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2776&p=.htm| archive-date= May 20, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The film remained in the top ten for the fourth weekend in a row, grossing approximately $2,285,000 and finished eighth for the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=21&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office: May 21\u201323, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 23, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100525231015/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=21&p=.htm| archive-date= May 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In its fifth weekend, the film fell out of the box office top ten and finished eleventh with an estimated $910,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=22&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office: May 28\u201330, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 31, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100601034148/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=22&p=.htm| archive-date= June 1, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs of July 6, 2010, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' has earned $63,071,122 at the domestic box office.<ref name=\"mojo\" /> With its $63 million in domestic box office, ''A Nightmare On Elm Street'' was the second-highest-grossing film among slasher remakes of the time\u2014''[[When a Stranger Calls (2006 film)|When a Stranger Calls]]'' (2006), ''[[Black Christmas (2006 film)|Black Christmas]]'' (2006), ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]'' (2007), ''[[Prom Night (2008 film)|Prom Night]]'' (2008), and ''[[My Bloody Valentine 3D]]'' (2009); ''[[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' (2009) was first with $65 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=slasherremakevs.htm |title=Slasher Remake |website=BoxOfficeMojo.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-15}}</ref> The film was officially released overseas on May 8, 2010. In its opening weekend, it took in approximately $6.5 million throughout ten foreign territories. It also secured first place for the weekend at the Russian box office with $3 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2769&p=.htm|author=Ray Subers|title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Iron Man 2' Battles Depreciating Euro|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|date=May 11, 2010|accessdate=May 12, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100515103706/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2769&p=.htm| archive-date= May 15, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Since its opening, the film has taken in approximately $52,332,285 in the overseas box office giving it a worldwide total gross of $115,407,296.<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n\nThe 2010 remake's opening weekend put it ahead of the box office grosses for ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge]]'' ($29,999,213), ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' ($25,504,513), ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child]]'' ($22,168,359), and ''[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare]]'' ($18,090,181).<ref name=\"Nightcomp\" /> <!-- When adjusting the opening weekend for the 1984 original for 2010 inflation, the remake out grossed Wes Craven's film $32,902,299 to $2,736,653.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.halfhill.com/inflation1.html|title=Tom's Inflation Calculator|publisher=Half Hill|accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref>--> When breaking the inflation-adjusted grosses down by per theater capita, the 1984 film averaged $16,585 per cinema compared to the remake's $9,874.<ref>Simple Averaging (Total opening gross/Number of theaters). For ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' (1984), the adjusted inflation gross was used over the unadjusted amount.</ref> Comparing the film to other Platinum Dunes remakes, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' is second in opening-weekend gross behind ''Friday the 13th'' with $40,570,365.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fridaythe13th09.htm |title=''Friday the 13th'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216104549/http://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fridaythe13th09.htm |archive-date=December 16, 2009 }}</ref> The film sits ahead of the other Platinum Dunes remakes, which includes ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (2003 film)|The Texas Chainsaw Massacre]]'' ($28,094,014),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tcm03.htm |title=''The Texas Chainsaw Massacre'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090116/https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tcm03.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> ''[[The Amityville Horror (2005 film)|The Amityville Horror]]'' ($23,507,007),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=amityvillehorror05.htm |title=''The Amityville Horror'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090157/https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=amityvillehorror05.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> and ''[[The Hitcher (2007 film)|The Hitcher]]'' ($7,818,239).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hitcher07.htm |title=''The Hitcher'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090202/https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hitcher07.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> As of 2018, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' is number nineteen on the list of top opening weekends for the month of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=04&p=.htm|title=Top Opening Weekends By Month|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 2, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100504135210/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=04&p=.htm| archive-date= May 4, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the remake is ninth in slasher films and eighth in horror remakes for all-time-highest-grossing films (unadjusted dollars).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=slasher.htm|title=Horror \u2013 Slasher: 1970 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100523000829/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=slasher.htm| archive-date= May 23, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=horrorremake.htm|title=Horror Remakes: 1982 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527153753/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=horrorremake.htm| archive-date= May 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> When comparing its opening weekends to other slasher films and horror remakes, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' sits in fifth spots for both categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=slasher.htm&p=.htm|title=Horror \u2013 Slasher Opening Weekend: 1982 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100524023816/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=slasher.htm&p=.htm| archive-date= May 24, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=horrorremake.htm&p=.htm|title=Horror Remakes Opening Weekend: 1982 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100506194807/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=horrorremake.htm&p=.htm| archive-date= May 6, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The 2010 remake was the second-highest-grossing film in the franchise in North America, just behind ''[[Freddy vs. Jason]]'' (unadjusted dollars) but number one worldwide.<ref name=\"Nightcomp\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' has an approval rating of 15% based on 178 reviews, with an average rating of 3.75/10.<ref name=\"tomatoes\" /> The site's critics consensus reads, \"Visually faithful but lacking the depth and subversive twists that made the original so memorable, the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' remake lives up to its title in the worst possible way.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/nightmare_on_elm_street_2010/ |title= A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010) |publisher= [[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006154017/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/nightmare_on_elm_street_2010/ |archive-date=October 6, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 35 out of 100 based on 25 reviews.<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/a-nightmare-on-elm-street|title=''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' (2010): Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=CNET Networks|accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] polls reported that the average grade cinemagoers gave the film was a \"C+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nicole Sperling|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/02/nightmare-box-office-furry-vengeance/|title=Box Office:'Nightmare' scares up $32 million; 'Furry Vengeance' can't cross $7 million|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=May 2, 2010|accessdate=May 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504214423/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/02/nightmare-box-office-furry-vengeance/|archive-date=May 4, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Their exit polls showed that audiences were evenly divided between males and females with 40% between 18 and 24 years of age and 20% under 18.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brandon Gray|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2751&p=.htm|title='Nightmare' Wakes Up in Top Spot|publisher=Internet Movie Database|work=Box Office Mojo|date=May 2, 2010|accessdate=May 3, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100504230500/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2751&p=.htm| archive-date= May 4, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a B\u2013 and concluded that, \"I did jump a few times, and I liked Haley's dour malevolence, but overall, the new ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' is a by-the-numbers bad dream that plays a little too much like a corporately ordered rerun. One, two, Freddy's coming for you. Three, four, we've been there before.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20365198,00.html|title=A Nightmare On Elm Street|author-link= Owen Gleiberman| last= Gleiberman |first= Owen|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=April 29, 2010}}</ref> Michael Rechtshaffen of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' criticized the acting as \"lethargically lifeless\" and criticized Haley's portrayal of Krueger saying, \"Even with his electronically deepened voice and a pointless amount of backstory, there's just no replacing Englund.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/a-nightmare-elm-street-film-29537|title=A Nightmare on Elm Street \u2013 Film Review|last=Rechtshaffen|first=Michael|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]] |date=October 14, 2010|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film one star out of four because he \"stared at ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' with weary resignation. The movie consists of a series of teenagers who are introduced, haunted by nightmares and then slashed to death by Freddy. So what? Are we supposed to be scared? Is the sudden clanging chord supposed to evoke a fearful [[Classical conditioning|Pavlovian]] response?\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/a-nightmare-on-elm-street-2010 |title=A Nightmare on Elm Street review|last= Ebert |first= Roger|author-link=Roger Ebert|work=Chicago Sun-Times|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]] |date= April 28, 2010|accessdate= May 5, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nOn January 5, 2011, the film won the [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award]] for best horror film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gossipcop.com/peoples-choice-awards-winners-fans-vote-favorite-2011/ |title=People's Choice Awards winners &#124; People's Choice Awards 2011 |publisher=Gossip Cop |date=January 5, 2011 |accessdate=July 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/658fneAgx?url=http://www.gossipcop.com/peoples-choice-awards-winners-fans-vote-favorite-2011/ |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010 film)}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.nightmareonelmstreet.com/}}\n* {{AllRovi title|430365|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n* {{Mojo title|nightmareonelmstreet10|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n* {{IMDb title|1179056|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n* [http://www.metacritic.com/movie/a-nightmare-on-elm-street/ ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''] at [[Metacritic]]\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|nightmare_on_elm_street_2010|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n\n{{A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n{{Platinum Dunes}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nightmare On Elm Street}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010 horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s ghost films]]\n[[Category:2010s teen horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s slasher films]]\n[[Category:American film remakes]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American ghost films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:American teen horror films]]\n[[Category:American slasher films]]\n[[Category:A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:D-Box motion-enhanced films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Horror film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Platinum Dunes films]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael Bay]]\n[[Category:Films about child abuse]]\n[[Category:Films about nightmares]]\n[[Category:Films about pedophilia]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about sleep disorders]]\n[[Category:Films about suburbia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Ohio]]\n[[Category:New Line Cinema films|Nightmare on Elm Street (2010 film)]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Reboot films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steve Jablonsky]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Bradley Fuller]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Andrew Form]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Samuel Bayer]]\n[[Category:2010 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Nightmare on Elm Street\n| image          = A Nightmare on Elm Street 2010 poster.jpg\n| alt            = Movie poster of a man with a hat, looking down; the man's skin and clothes are heavily burnt; one bladed finger shows through clasped hands\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Samuel Bayer]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Bay]]\n* [[Andrew Form]]\n* [[Bradley Fuller|Brad Fuller]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Wesley Strick]]\n* [[Eric Heisserer]]\n}}\n| story          = Wesley Strick\n| based on       = {{basedon|Characters|[[Wes Craven]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jackie Earle Haley]]\n* [[Kyle Gallner]]\n* [[Rooney Mara]]\n* [[Katie Cassidy]]\n* [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]]\n* [[Kellan Lutz]]<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Steve Jablonsky]]\n| cinematography = Jeff Cutter\n| editing        = [[Glen Scantlebury]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Platinum Dunes]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[New Line Cinema]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|04|27|[[Hollywood]]|ref1=<ref>{{cite web|author=Hollywood.com Staff |url=http://www.hollywood.com/photos/misc/6844969/a-nightmare-on-elm-street-world-premiere#218272/0 |title=\"A Nightmare On Elm Street\" World Premiere |website=Hollywood.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-28}}</ref>|2010|04|30|United States|2010|05|7|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $35 million<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| gross          = $115.6 million<ref>{{cite web|title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=August 1, 2011| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110624060958/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm| archive-date= June 24, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>  <!--NOTE: Please update the figures at the bottom of the page in the Box Office section, as well as the Accessdate in the Citation Template. Thank you.-->\n}}\n\n'''''A Nightmare on Elm Street''''' is a 2010 American [[slasher film]] directed by [[Samuel Bayer]], and written by [[Wesley Strick]] and [[Eric Heisserer]]. The film stars [[Jackie Earle Haley]], [[Kyle Gallner]], [[Rooney Mara]], [[Katie Cassidy]], [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]], and [[Kellan Lutz]]. It is a [[remake]] of [[Wes Craven]]'s [[A Nightmare on Elm Street|1984 film of the same name]]. Produced by [[Michael Bay]] and [[Platinum Dunes]], the film was designed to reboot the [[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|''Nightmare on Elm Street'' franchise]] and is the ninth installment in the series. The film is set in a [[Fictional location|fictitious town]] of Ohio and centers around a group of teenagers living on one street who are stalked and murdered in their dreams by a disfigured man named [[Freddy Krueger]]. The teenagers discover that they all share a common link from their childhood that makes them targets for Krueger.\n\n''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was originally to follow the same design as Platinum Dunes' other remake, ''[[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|Friday the 13th]]'', where the writers took the best elements from each of the films in the original series and created a single storyline with them. Eventually, they decided to use Craven's original storyline but tried to create a scarier film. To that end, they decided to remove the one-line quipping Freddy, who had become less scary and more comical over the years, and bring back his darker nature. The writers developed the character to be a child molester, something that Craven wanted to do originally in 1984 but changed to a child killer instead. Freddy's physical appearance was changed with the use of computer-generated imagery to be closer to that of a burn victim. Because of the positive experiences Platinum Dunes' producers had in the area, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was filmed primarily in Illinois. Craven expressed his displeasure when he was not consulted on the project. [[Robert Englund]], who portrayed Freddy in the previous eight films, voiced his support of the remake and the casting of Haley in the role of Freddy.\n\n''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' had its world premiere at Hollywood on April 27, 2010, and was theatrically released in North America on April 30, 2010, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] and [[New Line Cinema]]. The film received generally negative reviews from critics, who criticized the teenage characters and story while offering some praise for Bayer's direction and Haley's performance. Despite this, it was box-office success, earned over $63 million at the domestic box office and over $115 million worldwide, making it the highest-grossing film in the franchise and the highest-grossing slasher film in unadjusted dollars.\n\n==Plot==\n<!--STOP. Wikipedia is not a substitute for watching a movie, and plot summaries should not contain every minor detail. They are here to SUMMARIZE the basic events. For a horror movie, we don't need to explain how every single character was killed, and what everyone is doing that isn't relevant to the overall plot. Thank you. !-->\n[[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Kris Fowles|Kris Fowles]] meets her friend, Dean Russell, at the Springwood Diner. Dean falls asleep at the table and dreams that he meets a severely burned man in seared clothes who has a bladed gardener's glove on his right hand. The man cuts Dean's throat in the dream, but it appears to Kris and their classmate, waitress [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Nancy Holbrook|Nancy Holbrook]], that Dean cuts himself. At Dean's funeral, Kris sees a photograph of her and Dean as children, but cannot recall knowing Dean before high school. Kris begins to dream about the burned man, then refuses to go to sleep for fear that she will die like Dean. Jesse Braun, Kris's ex-boyfriend, shows up to keep her company while she sleeps, but Kris meets the burned man in her dreams and is murdered. Covered in Kris's blood, Jesse runs to Nancy's house and learns that Nancy has been having nightmares about the same man\u2014[[Freddy Krueger|Freddy]]. Jesse tells Nancy that they need to stop Freddy and warns her not to fall asleep, then runs off.\n\nJesse is arrested by the police under suspicion of murdering Kris. He tries not to fall asleep in his jail cell but fails, and is killed by Freddy. As her friends die, Nancy questions everyone's connection to each other, given that none of them can remember each other before their teenage years. Nancy and her friend Quentin Smith discover that all of them attended Badham Preschool. Nancy's mother, Gwen, reluctantly tells Nancy and Quentin that there was a groundskeeper at the preschool, Fred Krueger, who was accused of [[child sexual abuse|sexually abusing]] the children. Gwen explains that Nancy was his favorite, and that she came home one day and told her mother about the things Krueger did to her in a secret room. Gwen alerted the other parents, including Quentin's father Alan, and Kris's mother Nora, but she tells the teenagers that Krueger escaped before he was arrested. Nancy does not believe her and attempts to track down the remaining kids from the school. She discovers that all of the other kids have been killed, most of them in their sleep, and after Jesse\u2019s death, only she and Quentin are left.\n\nQuentin tries to accept that his nightmares are nothing more than repressed memories, but he falls asleep during swim practice and witnesses what really happened to Krueger\u2014the parents tracked him down and burned him alive. Quentin and Nancy believe that Krueger, now a [[vengeful ghost]], wants revenge on them for lying as children. As a result of their [[insomnia]], they have sporadic [[microsleep]] episodes and become [[hypnagogia|hypnagogic]]. To try to stop Krueger, they decide to go to the preschool to learn what they can. On the way, Nancy is attacked by Krueger after a microsleep episode, but she pulls a piece of Krueger's sweater out of the dream world into reality. Quentin takes Nancy to the hospital where he steals [[epinephrine|adrenaline]] to help them stay awake. Finally at the preschool, they uncover Krueger's hidden room and the evidence that proves he did indeed abuse all of the children; they then realize that Kreuger wants revenge on them for telling the truth.\n\nNancy decides to pull Krueger out of the dream world and kill him in the real world. Quentin tries to stay awake long enough to pull Nancy out of her dream when she grabs Krueger, but he falls asleep and is attacked. Krueger goes after Nancy and explains that he deliberately left her for last so she would stay awake long enough to become comatose. Quentin awakens and uses the adrenaline to wake Nancy, who then pulls Krueger into reality. They fight and Nancy uses a broken paper cutter blade to kill him before she torches the secret room with Krueger's body inside. Nancy and Quentin escape. However, Krueger's remains are not found by the fire fighters who put out the fire. After Nancy and her mother return home from the hospital, Krueger suddenly appears.  While Nancy screams, Krueger kills Nancy's mother before pulling her body through a mirror and then disappearing.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Main|List of cast members of the Nightmare on Elm Street series|List of A Nightmare on Elm Street characters}}\n{{div col begin}}\n* [[Jackie Earle Haley]] as [[Freddy Krueger|Fred \"Freddy\" Krueger]]\n* [[Kyle Gallner]] as Quentin Smith\n* [[Rooney Mara]] as [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Nancy Holbrook|Nancy Holbrook]]\n**Kyra Krumins as young Nancy\n* [[Katie Cassidy]] as [[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)#Kris Fowles|Kris Fowles]]\n**Julianna Damm as young Kris\n* [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]] as Jesse Braun\n**Bayden Coyer as young Jesse\n* [[Kellan Lutz]] as Dean Russell\n**Max Holt as young Dean\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as Alan Smith \n* [[Connie Britton]] as Dr. Gwen Holbrook\n* Lia Mortensen as Nora Fowles\n* [[Kurt Naebig]] as Mr. Russell\n* Jennifer Robers as Mrs. Russell\n* [[Christian Stolte]] as Mr. Braun\n* [[Aaron Yoo]] as Marcus Yeon (uncredited) \n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn January 29, 2008, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Michael Bay]] and his [[Platinum Dunes]] production company would reboot the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' franchise with a remake of [[A Nightmare on Elm Street|the original 1984 film]].<ref name=\"NightAnno\">{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Michael|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979807.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=New Line sets up new 'Nightmare'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=January 29, 2008|accessdate=January 29, 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120529175832/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979807?refCatId=13|archive-date=May 29, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Producer Brad Fuller explained that they would follow the same tactic from their [[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|''Friday the 13th'' remake<!--STOP. Form and Fuller have consistently referred to the film as a \"remake\"!-->]]<nowiki/> and would abandon the things that had made the series less scary\u2014the film's antagonist, [[Freddy Krueger]], would not be \"cracking jokes\" as had become a staple of his character . The focus would be to \"make a horrifying movie\". Fuller said that the film would be a remake of the 1984 film, but clarified that they would borrow character deaths and dream sequences from the entire series.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=8835|title=Nightmare on Elm Street is Go, Shooting in Spring|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=December 11, 2008|accessdate=June 20, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212163646/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=8835|archive-date=December 12, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' announced that [[Samuel Bayer]] was hired to direct the film.<ref name=\"Director\">{{cite news|url=http://riskybusiness.hollywoodreporter.com/2009/02/11/a-director-moves-onto-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |last=Zeitchik |first=Steven |title=A director moves onto (Nightmare on) Elm Street |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]] |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=February 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517041553/http://riskybusiness.hollywoodreporter.com/2009/02/11/a-director-moves-onto-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |archive-date=May 17, 2010 }}</ref> According to New Line production chief Toby Emmerich, Michael Bay advocated heavily for Bayer because he had \"the ability to capture the kind of seductive and unsettling imagery that would make ''Nightmare'' feel like a fresh, visually arresting moviegoing experience.\"<ref name=\"LAint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-bigpicture14-2009jul14,0,698071.story|title='Nightmare on Elm Street' returns|last=Goldstein|first=Patrick|date=July 14, 2009|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> Bayer declined Platinum Dunes' offer twice but finally accepted after Bay emailed him and explained the kind of business opportunity it would be.<ref name=\"Bayerint\">{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=14330|title=1:1 With Nightmare on Elm Street's Sam Bayer|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=CraveOnline|date=March 2, 2010|accessdate=March 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306114246/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=14330|archive-date=March 6, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 95%; background:#F0F8FF; color:black; width:30em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"It's definitely not a standard slasher film. This is a movie that you can mention to people and their jaws drop ... because of that franchise, that character, had a profound effect on their childhood. ... I hear things like, 'Freddy scared the hell out of me.' ... What everyone involved wants to do is re-invent the character for a new generation.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014 Samuel Bayer on remaking ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''.<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n|}\nIn a June 9, 2009 interview, Craven, who directed the original movie and was not consulted for the remake, expressed displeasure with the new film.<ref name=\"Cravenint\">{{cite news|last=Parfitt|first=Orlando|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/992/992845p1.html|title=Craven's Elm Street Nightmare Exclusive: Original director angry over remake.|work=[[IGN Entertainment]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=June 9, 2009|accessdate=June 19, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612044359/http://movies.ign.com/articles/992/992845p1.html|archive-date=June 12, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> In contrast, [[Robert Englund]], who portrayed Freddy throughout the film series, felt it was time for ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' to be remade. Englund liked the idea of being able to \"exploit the dreamscape\" with computer-generated imagery and other technologies that did not exist when Craven made the original in 1984.<ref name=\"Englundint\">{{cite news|last=McCabe|first=Joseph|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b15904_exclusive_robert_englund_on_jackie.html|title=Robert Englund on Jackie Earle Haley and the 'Nightmare' Remake!|work=[[FEARnet]]|publisher=Horror Entertainment|date=June 27, 2009|accessdate=June 29, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701121100/http://www.fearnet.com/news/b15904_exclusive_robert_englund_on_jackie.html|archive-date=July 1, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Bayer believes that his film paid homage to what Craven did in 1984, but did not replicate it entirely. Bayer recognized that Craven attempted to put more meaning into his films and that the character of Freddy Krueger affected the lives of a generation of people. For Bayer, remaking ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was about bringing that feeling to a new generation with a new spin on the character and story.<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n\nFuller and Form likened the new film to their [[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (2003 film)|2003 remake of ''The Texas Chain Saw Massacre'']] but instead of a remake, they saw it as more of a reimagining.<ref name=\"setpreview\">{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11115|title=Set Visit Preview: A Nightmare on Elm Street|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=CraveOnline|date=July 21, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090723081206/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11115|archive-date=July 23, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The pair also explained that ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' would have a different tone than their ''Friday the 13th'' remake. Form states, \"I think a ''Friday the 13th'' movie like we made was really fun. You know, sex, drugs and rock and roll, and I think a Nightmare movie is not that.\"<ref name=\"SiFi\">{{cite news|url=http://scifiwire.com/2009/07/join-us-behind-the-scenes.php|title=UPDATED: Behind the scenes of the new Nightmare on Elm Street|last=Gilchrist|first=Todd|date=July 22, 2009|work=[[Sci-Fi Wire]]|publisher=[[SyFy]]|accessdate=July 30, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104221257/http://blastr.com/2009/07/join-us-behind-the-scenes.php|archive-date=January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked why New Line was rebooting the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' film series, Emmerich explained, \"The Nightmare films are profoundly disturbing on a deep, human level because they're about our dreams. It's why we thought that we could reach an especially broad audience with a new film, since the feeling of having your dreams being invaded was something that would translate to any country and any culture.\"<ref name=\"LAint\"/> Overall, Bayer wanted to create a film in \"a darker world\" that made the audience ask, \"What makes a monster?\"\u2014is it a monster because of its physical appearance, someone with a scarred face and a clawed glove, or is it a monster because of something deeper within the man himself.<ref name=\"Rotint\"/>\n\n===Writing===\nWesley Strick was initially hired to pen a script for a new ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' because he had impressed Emmerich with a prequel script he wrote for the 1995 film ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Seven]]''. Eric Heisserer was subsequently hired to provide a rewrite of Strick's script before the film moved into production.<ref name=\"LAint\"/> When Bayer came on board he received a script that reflected the combined efforts of Strick and Heisserer and which still \"needed to be tinkered with\". Bayer explained that the script goes deeper into \"[Freddy] as a person [and] how he became the thing he was\". Bayer expressed that unlike the ''Friday the 13th'' remake that picked the best parts from the first four films, the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' remake was coming straight from the first film.<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n\nFor the remake, Freddy was brought back to his darker roots and away from the comical character he had become in later ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' sequels. Fuller pointed out that this Freddy did have one-liners but they come from a darker sense of humor and were not intended to be as campy as in previous films. Craven's original characterization of Freddy as a [[Child sexual abuse|child molester]] was used because if Freddy killed children, as in the original, it would have been easy for the teenage characters to figure out using the Internet what had happened.<ref name=\"Bloodint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19996|title=Producer Brad Fuller Talks 'A Nightmare on Elm Street'|author=Chris Eggertsen|date=April 28, 2010|work=Bloody Disgusting|accessdate=April 29, 2010|publisher=The Collective}}</ref> In an effort to keep the story fresh, Heisserer developed the concept of micro-naps because the dream-reality sequences could become repetitive. The micro-nap allowed them to \"blur reality and the dream world, and get some great scares\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19219|title=Set Visit: A Trip to 'A Nightmare on Elm Street' Part One|work=Bloody Disgusting|publisher=The Collective|date=February 22, 2010|accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n{{Wide image|A Nightmare on Elm Street panel at WonderCon 2010 1.JPG|450px|The cast at [[WonderCon]] 2010. From left to right: Dekker, Cassidy, Mara, Gallner, and Haley.|box width|right|alt=Five actors from the cast, sitting at a long table, each with a microphone. The backdrop has the WonderCon logo. The actors from left to right are Dekker, Cassidy, Mara, Gallner, and Haley.}}\nIn February 2009, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' revealed Robert Englund would not reprise the role of Freddy Krueger for the remake; Englund had performed the role for the eight previous films.<ref name=\"Director\"/> On April 3, 2009 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' reported that [[Jackie Earle Haley]] was cast to take over Englund's most well-known role.<ref name=\"Haleyanno\">{{cite news|last=Rich|first=Joshua|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/nightmare-haley.html|title='Nightmare on Elm Street' reboot: Jackie Earle Haley to play Freddy Krueger|work=Hollywood Insider|date=April 3, 2009|accessdate=April 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405090144/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/nightmare-haley.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 5, 2009}}</ref> Initially, the studio wanted to cast an unknown for the role of Freddy Krueger, but it was Haley's performance in ''[[Little Children (film)|Little Children]]'' that impressed Emmerich enough to cast the actor against the original intentions. Emmerich explained, \"Freddy is this incredible stew of malevolence and anger, but he also has a hint of vulnerability, and Jackie really has all of that and more. He just seemed completely right for the part.\"<ref name=\"LAint\"/> Bayer stated that he and producers Form and Fuller managed to acquire the screen test Haley gave as [[Rorschach (comics)|Rorschach]] for ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]''; after viewing it, Bayer said it \"blew [his] mind\", and that he knew Haley would be able to go deep and create a believable character who was a psychopath \"with a burned face and a claw.\"<ref name=\"Bayerint\"/>\n\nHaley said the first time he heard his name mentioned in conjunction with the character was from people on the Internet who suggested he be cast. Later he learned that his agents were already in talks with Brad Fuller.<ref name=\"MTVint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1625034/nightmare-on-elm-street-new-freddy-krueger-thanks-fans-for-casting/|title='Nightmare On Elm Street' New Freddy Krueger Thanks Fans For Casting|last=Carroll|first=Larry|date=October 31, 2009|work=MTV|accessdate=April 29, 2010|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]}}</ref> Haley stated that he was apprehensive about taking on the role of a character with such a dark past\u2014that of a child murderer\u2014for about a \"minute and a half\". Knowing the Freddy Krueger in the remake would be even darker, Haley came quickly to the realization that he was doing a horror film and this was just a fictional character. Haley said that once he embraced the idea of Freddy as a \"mythical boogeyman\", it became \"very freeing\" for him as an actor.<ref name=\"Rotint\">{{cite news|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=15025|title=Video Interviews: A Nightmare on Elm Street|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=CraveOnline|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=April 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504051934/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=15025|archive-date=May 4, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 95%; background:#F0F8FF; color:black; width:28em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"Jackie is not big, and I think that Jackie's size is gonna really work ... one of the metaphors ... I've used for Freddy is a little rabid dog that just bites your ankle and holds on ... and I think Jackie brings that, with his own physicality, to the role, without ever having to work it a little bit.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014 Robert Englund on Jackie Earle Haley as Freddy Krueger.<ref name=\"Englundint\"/>\n|}\nHaley is contracted for three films which includes the remake and two sequels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jackie Earle Haley Signed on for Three ''Elm Street'' Films!|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16621|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=July 1, 2009|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> Englund stated he agreed with the casting of Haley and that he feels Haley's physical size works in this role.<ref name=\"Englundint\"/> Haley stated that he did not intend to have Englund's original performances influence his own and that he used the frustration of having to sit in the make-up chair for three-and-a-half hours as his motivation to get into character.<ref name=\"setpreview\"/>\n\n[[Rooney Mara]] plays the role of Nancy Holbrook;<ref name=\"theindependent\">{{cite news |title= Classic horror film 'A Nightmare On Elm Street' gets updated|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/classic-horror-film-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-gets-updated-1956347.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=April 28, 2010|accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref> Mara is also contracted for a sequel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rooney Mara Signed on For ''Elm Street'' Sequel|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16566|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=June 24, 2009|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> Bayer describes Nancy as \"the loneliest girl in the world\".<ref name=\"prodnote\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nightmareonelmstreet.com/media/downloads/NOES_ProdNotes.pdf|title=Production Notes from ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''|publisher=Official Nightmare on Elm Street website|format=PDF|accessdate=April 24, 2010}}</ref> Mara stated that her Nancy is different than the role of [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy Thompson]], performed by Heather Langenkamp, and described her character as \"socially awkward and timid and really doesn't know how to connect with people\".<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> [[Kyle Gallner]] was cast as Quentin, who forms a connection with Nancy. Gallner described his character as \"a mess, more jittery and more 'out there' than Nancy is\".<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Gallner pointed out that his character is like this because of the amount of pharmaceuticals he ingests to stay awake. Producer Brad Fuller commented that Gallner brought a sense of \"humanity and relatability\" to the role with his compassion and intellect.<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Other cast members include [[Katie Cassidy]], [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]], and [[Kellan Lutz]]. Cassidy performed the role of Kris. According to Cassidy, Kris becomes an emotional wreck throughout the film. Cassidy described her character's ordeal: \"She is literally dragged through hell, having to crawl through dark, claustrophobic tunnels. She's always crying and freaking out as her nightmares of Freddy bleed into her everyday life. Kris suspects there's something that connects her with the others; she even confronts her mother about it, but no one's talking.\"<ref name=\"prodnote\"/>\n\nDekker portrays Jesse, Kris's ex-boyfriend. According to Dekker, \"Jesse kind of knows what's going on but refuses to believe it.\"<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Dekker explained that Jesse spends so much time trying to convince himself that Freddy is not real, that by the time he does meet Freddy face-to-face, \"he's just a mess. ... There's no bravado about it. His terror is very real.\"<ref name=\"prodnote\"/> Lutz plays Dean, Kris's current boyfriend and \"a well-liked, well-off high school jock.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Vary |first=Adam |title=''Twilight'' star Kellan Lutz in final talks to join ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' |url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/24/kellan-lutz-elm/ |work=Hollywood Insider |date=April 23, 2009 |accessdate=May 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010144152/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/04/24/kellan-lutz-elm/ |archive-date=October 10, 2009 }}</ref> [[Connie Britton]], [[Clancy Brown]] and [[Elvis Jasso Mar\u00edn]] also star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/NEFCOFHFXdTdJN|title=First Look at Freddy Krueger and the New Poster for A Nightmare on Elm Street|date=July 22, 2009|work=Movie Web|publisher=[[Comcast|Comcast Digital]]|accessdate=May 5, 2010}}</ref> Gallner and Mara explained that the teenagers in the remake are \"a little more aware\" of Freddy and their situation, whereas in the original Nancy and her friends were \"more mellow\" and \"nonchalant\"  until they were finally killed.<ref name=\"Rotint\"/>\n\n===Krueger's design===\n[[File:Freddy Krueger (Jackie Earle Haley).jpg|thumb|Haley wore prosthetic appliances on his face that were blended together to appear seamless and designed to look close to an actual burn victim. [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] was used on portions of his face\u2014like his cheek\u2014that appear open.|alt=A picture of the face of a man with severe burns. Parts of skin are burned through and appear hollow. The head has a hit and the glove with finger knives is in the forefront. ]]\nForm and Fuller explained that Freddy's physical appearance would more accurately resemble a burn victim.<ref name=\"SiFi\"/> Form later clarified that there was a fine line they did not want to cross when it came to making Freddy look like a burn victim. According to the producer, the crew had many reference photos of burn victims which detailed how white the skin would appear after healing. Form did not want the audience to turn away in disgust every time Freddy was on the screen, so they opted to hold back on some of the realism. Fuller noted how horrific the images were and how difficult they were to look at.<ref name=\"Shockset\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=14163|title=Set Visit: A Nightmare Reborn on Elm Street|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|date=February 22, 2010|work=Shock Till You Drop|accessdate=May 2, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313183639/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=14163|archive-date=February 2, 2013|url-status=dead|publisher=CraveOnline}}</ref> The special effects crew that worked on ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' and created the computer-generated images (CGI) for [[Two-Face]], were brought in to work on the CGI for Freddy's face. The CGI is used in conjunction with the special effects make-up that Haley wears.<ref name=\"Rotint\"/> The prosthetic appliances used to create Freddy's physical look were designed by Andrew Clement. Haley described the experience of wearing the prosthetic devices and make-up as \"pretty encumbering\".<ref name=\"fearint\">{{cite news|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b18350_Jackie_Earle_Haley_Talks_Playing_Freddy_Krueger.html|title=Jackie Earle Haley Talks Playing Freddy Krueger|work=FEARnet|publisher=Horror Entertainment|last=Raffel|first=Lawrence P.|date=March 3, 2010|accessdate=April 29, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120405123611/http://www.fearnet.com/news/b18350_Jackie_Earle_Haley_Talks_Playing_Freddy_Krueger.html|archive-date=April 5, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhen production started, Clement and his crew would spend six hours applying Haley's make-up; eventually, the crew was able to streamline the process.<ref name=\"Shockset\"/> According to Haley, the make-up crew would glue individual prosthetic devices from his head all the way down his back. The appliances were then blended together to create a seamless appearance. Haley spent approximately three hours and twenty minutes each day in the make-up chair to apply the appliances; on occasion, it would take almost four-and-a-half hours when the crew also needed to apply the prosthetic skull cap. Haley did not need to worry about the skull cap most days because he was able to wear the fedora on top of his head. Haley also had to wear contact lenses\u2014one bloody, one cloudy. The cloudy contact lens made it difficult for the actor to see.<ref name=\"fearint\"/> Haley also had to work on developing Freddy's voice for the film. According to Haley, the process of coming up with the perfect voice for Freddy was \"this organic process of embodying the character\", and not about just \"sitting around the table and going, 'Let me try this voice and this voice{{'\"}}. Haley and Bayer admitted that some of the voice would be digitally enhanced to give it a \"supernatural quality\" and differentiate it from the voice Haley used as [[Rorschach (comics)|Rorschach]] in ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]''.<ref name=\"SDCC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=11247|last=Rotten|first=Ryan|title=SDCC Press Conference: A Nightmare on Elm Street|publisher=Crave Online Media|work=Shock Till You Drop|date=July 30, 2009|accessdate=April 30, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008181750/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=11247|archive-date=October 8, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Budding Film Industry in Gary, Indiana.jpg|thumb|left|Filming at former City Methodist Church in [[Gary, Indiana]].|alt=Six lights on a rig lighting up and in front of a Gothic Revival style church building.]]\nWith a budget of $35 million,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/04/nightmare-to-rule-at-home-while-iron-man-explodes-overseas.html|title=Movie projector: 'Nightmare' to rule at home with $30 million while 'Iron Man 2' explodes to $100 million-plus overseas|last= Fritz|first=Ben|date=April 29, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=April 30, 2010|quote=The new \"Nightmare\" isn't expected to do quite that well but should still be a solid performer for the studio given its production budget of about $35 million.}}</ref> [[principal photography]] began on May 5, 2009, and officially [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] on July 10, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.qconline.com/archives/qco/display.php?id=436859|title=2 Chicago-area schools to be horror movie sites|publisher=Quad Cities Online|agency=Associated Press|date=April 27, 2009|accessdate=April 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11047|title=That's a Wrap on Nightmare on Elm Street|work=Shock Till You Drop|publisher=[[Bradley Fuller|Brad Fuller]]|date=July 10, 2009|accessdate=July 10, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090712071815/http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11047|archive-date=July 12, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Because of the positive experiences Platinum Dunes' producers had in the area when producing ''The Amityville Horror'' and ''The Unborn'', they chose to film in Illinois. Platinum Dunes also received a thirty percent tax break for filming in the state. The producers looked for locations that were \"old and decaying\" to mirror the look of Krueger. They settled on the Ryerson Steel warehouse on the west side of Chicago to film most of the scenes in which the townspeople burn Krueger alive.<ref name=\"10quest\">{{cite news|last=Arroyave|first=Luis|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/chi-091030-nightmare-elm-questions-pictures,0,6957467.photogallery|title=10 questions about new 'Nightmare on Elm Street' answered|work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103095524/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/chi-091030-nightmare-elm-questions-pictures,0,6957467.photogallery|archive-date=November 3, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nNew Line contracted with two high schools in Illinois, [[Elk Grove High School (Elk Grove Village, Illinois)|Elk Grove High School]] and [[John Hersey High School]], to shoot scenes for the remake. According to Nancy Holman, principal of Elk Grove High, the studio contacted schools across the nation looking for one that had a swimming pool. Although filming took place at both schools, neither was identified by name. The studio cast 200 extras for various school scenes, including one in the pool, but required that all students who auditioned be at least 16 years old.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zalusky|first=Steve|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/story/?id=289286|title=Freddie's coming to Elk Grove, Hersey high schools|work=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]|publisher=Paddock Publications|date=April 27, 2009|accessdate=May 6, 2009}}</ref> Lenore Gonzales Bragaw, school board president, was initially apprehensive about the deal as she disliked the idea of the studio filming \"scenes of violence\" at the schools; Bragaw agreed once she was assured that no one would be killed during the pool scenes.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Graydon Megan |author2= John Keilman|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-talk-nightmare-follomay01,0,7725616.story|title=Chicago school district won't look a gift 'Nightmare' in the mouth|work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Company|date=May 1, 2009|accessdate=May 7, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504135854/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-talk-nightmare-follomay01,0,7725616.story|archive-date=May 4, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 22, 2009, the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' film crew went on location to the city of [[Gary, Indiana]] to film scenes at a Methodist church. The studio had negotiated with the city for months before finally settling on a deal. According to Ben Clement, the executive director of the Gary Office of Film and Television, the studio was looking for \"an architectural style that would fit the story line of the film\". The film crew returned to the streets of Gary first in June to film a dream sequence that takes place on Elm Street and later in December to shoot some scenes in a diner.<ref>{{cite news|author=Staff|url=http://www.thetimesonline.com/articles/2009/05/21/updates/breaking_news/doc4a158020018cd165290762.txt|title=Gary set to be backdrop for scenes in Freddy Krueger remake|work=The Times |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=May 21, 2009|accessdate=June 20, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/105/1053106p1.html|title=Freddy's Nightmare Continues: Casting call notice online for additional Elm Street filming|last=Vejvoda|first=Jim|work=[[IGN Entertainment]]|publisher=News Corporation|date=December 8, 2009|accessdate=December 28, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120710061447/http://movies.ign.com/articles/105/1053106p1.html|archive-date=July 10, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Fuller and Form, Warner Bros. suggested ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' be released in [[3D film|3D]] because of the increased box office revenue of recent 3D films. It was the opinion of the Platinum Dunes producers that if a film was not initially conceived as 3D, then it should not be converted to 3D; Fuller and Form fought the studio to keep the remake 2D. Warner Bros. and Platinum Dunes came to agree that a 3D movie would not be \"the best version of the movie\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Weintraub|first=Steve|url=http://www.collider.com/2010/04/26/exclusive-interview-producers-andrew-form-and-brad-fuller-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-plus-updates-on-monster-squad-ouija-friday-the-13th-2-and-the-nightmare-blu-ray-will-have-a-6-minute-alternat/|title=Exclusive Interview: Platinum Dunes Producers Andrew Form and Brad Fuller ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''|website=Collider|date=April 26, 2010|accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe score to ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was composed by [[Steve Jablonsky]]<!-- http://www.hans-zimmer.com/index.php?rub=disco&id=926 --> and recorded by a 60-piece string ensemble of the [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]].<ref name=scoring>{{cite news|last=Goldwasser|first=Dan|url=http://www.scoringsessions.com/news/216/|title=Steve Jablonsky scores ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''|publisher=ScoringSessions.com|date=March 26, 2010|accessdate=March 26, 2010}}</ref> The movie soundtrack was released by [[WaterTower Music]] on April 27, 2010.<ref name=WaterTower>{{cite news|title=WaterTower Music to Release \"A Nightmare on Elm Street\" Feature Film Soundtrack on April 27, 2010|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/04/22/idUS225641+22-Apr-2010+BW20100422|accessdate=June 24, 2014|work=Reuters|publisher=Business Wire|date=April 22, 2010|location=Burbank, California|quote=\"A Nightmare on Elm Street\" is being distributed worldwide by Warner Bros. Pictures, a Warner Bros. Entertainment Company.}}</ref> [[Charles Bernstein (composer)|Charles Bernstein]]'s original ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' theme and \"Jump Rope\" rhyme, The Hit Crew's \"Un Homme Et Une Femme\", and [[The Everly Brothers]]' \"[[All I Have to Do Is Dream]]\" are heard in the film but only Bernstein's \"Jump Rope\" rhyme is included in the soundtrack.\n\n==Release==\n''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was released on April 30, 2010, to 3,332 theaters and approximately 4,700 screens,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2746&p=.htm|title=Weekend Briefing: 'Nightmare on Elm Street,' 'Furry Vengeance'|author=Brandon Gray|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|work=Box Office Mojo|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100501225750/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2746&p=.htm| archive-date= May 1, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> making it the twelfth-widest opening for an R-rated film in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/widestmpaa.htm?page=R&p=.htm|title=Widest Openings By MPAA Rating|publisher=Internet Movie Database|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=April 29, 2010}}</ref> Comparatively, the original ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was only released to 165 theaters at its opening on November 9, 1984 and by the end of its box office run its widest release was 380 theaters.<ref name=\"OrigNight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=elmst.htm|title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984) Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=April 29, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100501225248/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=elmst.htm| archive-date= May 1, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The 2010 remake holds the record for widest ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' release, beating out ''[[Freddy vs. Jason]]'' by 318 theaters.<ref name=\"Nightcomp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=nightmareonelmstreet.htm|title=Nightmare on Elm Street Filmography Comparison|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=April 29, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100504181150/http://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=nightmareonelmstreet.htm| archive-date= May 4, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on October 5, 2010. The DVD's only feature is a featurette, \"Freddy Krueger Reborn\". The Blu-ray special features include the DVD's featurette along with a deleted scene, an alternate opening and ending, and the Maniacle Movie Mode.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dvdactive.com/news/releases/a-nightmare-on-elm-street4.html | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (US \u2013 DVD R1  BD) in News \u2013 Releases at DVDActive | publisher=DVDActive | date=July 23, 2010 | accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nIn March 2010, the [[National Entertainment Collectibles Association]] (NECA) released two new Freddy Krueger action figures; one pre-burned Freddy with Jackie Earle Haley's likeness, and one based on the new burn design from the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' remake.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36392/necas-new-freddy-figure-all-fired-up|title=NECA's New Freddy Figure All Fired Up|work=DreadCentral.com|publisher=CraveOnline|date=March 13, 2010|accessdate=March 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826165157/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36392/necas-new-freddy-figure-all-fired-up|archive-date=August 26, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> NECA also released a replica of Freddy's clawed glove.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36548/neca-gives-us-a-better-look-freddys-glove-from-a-nightmare-elm-street-2010|title=NECA Gives Us a Better Look at Freddy's Glove From A Nightmare on Elm Street 2010|work=DreadCentral.com|publisher=CraveOnline|date=March 23, 2010|accessdate=March 23, 2010}}</ref> An online game was released in conjunction with the film\u2014the player attempts to keep a young girl awake using coffee, cold showers, self-mutilation, and other means, to keep her safe from Freddy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19482|title=Keep Her Awake in New 'Elm Street' Online Game|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=Bloody Disgusting|publisher=The Collective|date=March 16, 2010|accessdate=March 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nEarly estimates put ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''{{'}}s opening-day gross at approximately $15 million with a projected opening weekend of $35 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/01/box-office-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |last=Sperling |first=Nicole |title=Box office: Friday numbers put Freddy Krueger in top spot with a $15 million night |publisher=CNN |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=May 1, 2010 |accessdate=May 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503004518/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/01/box-office-nightmare-on-elm-street/ |archive-date=May 3, 2010 }}</ref> Included in the $15 million was the $1.6 million the film made from midnight showings on Thursday night from 1,000 theaters. As a result, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' broke the record for midnight openings for a horror film that was previously held by the ''[[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' remake in 2009 that grossed $1 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/05/freddys-a-dream-nightmare-on-elm-street-sets-record-for-horror-midnights-15m-17m-today-and-40m-weekend-predictions/|last=Finke|first=Nikki|title=Freddy's A (Rotten) Dream: 'Nightmare On Elm Street Opens To $15.8M Friday, $35M Weekend; 'Furry Vengeance' Bombs|publisher=Mail.com Media Corporation|work=Deadline.com|date=May 1, 2010|accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> Ultimately, the film finished its opening with $32,902,299, placing first for the weekend ahead of ''[[How to Train Your Dragon (film)|How to Train Your Dragon]]'' (6th week in release), ''[[Date Night]]'' (4th week in release), ''[[The Back-up Plan]]'' (2nd week in release), and ''[[Furry Vengeance]]'' (1st week in release).<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=18&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office: April 30 \u2013 May 2, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=May 2, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100505173625/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=18&p=.htm| archive-date= May 5, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' dropped 72 percent in its second weekend, earning $9,119,389. It dropped to second place behind the newly released ''[[Iron Man 2]]''.<ref name=\"weekend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm|title=Weekend Grosses|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 11, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100513064015/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=nightmareonelmstreet10.htm| archive-date= May 13, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The film dropped an additional 54 percent in its third week, bringing in $1.5 million, though it remained in the top 10 rankings for the weekend, placing sixth overall.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brandon Gray|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2776&p=.htm|title=Friday Report: 'Iron Man 2' Fends Off 'Robin Hood'|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|date=May 15, 2010|accessdate=May 16, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100520010951/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2776&p=.htm| archive-date= May 20, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The film remained in the top ten for the fourth weekend in a row, grossing approximately $2,285,000 and finished eighth for the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=21&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office: May 21\u201323, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 23, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100525231015/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=21&p=.htm| archive-date= May 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In its fifth weekend, the film fell out of the box office top ten and finished eleventh with an estimated $910,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=22&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office: May 28\u201330, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 31, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100601034148/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2010&wknd=22&p=.htm| archive-date= June 1, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs of July 6, 2010, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' has earned $63,071,122 at the domestic box office.<ref name=\"mojo\" /> With its $63 million in domestic box office, ''A Nightmare On Elm Street'' was the second-highest-grossing film among slasher remakes of the time\u2014''[[When a Stranger Calls (2006 film)|When a Stranger Calls]]'' (2006), ''[[Black Christmas (2006 film)|Black Christmas]]'' (2006), ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]'' (2007), ''[[Prom Night (2008 film)|Prom Night]]'' (2008), and ''[[My Bloody Valentine 3D]]'' (2009); ''[[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' (2009) was first with $65 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=slasherremakevs.htm |title=Slasher Remake |website=BoxOfficeMojo.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-15}}</ref> The film was officially released overseas on May 8, 2010. In its opening weekend, it took in approximately $6.5 million throughout ten foreign territories. It also secured first place for the weekend at the Russian box office with $3 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2769&p=.htm|author=Ray Subers|title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Iron Man 2' Battles Depreciating Euro|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|date=May 11, 2010|accessdate=May 12, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100515103706/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2769&p=.htm| archive-date= May 15, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Since its opening, the film has taken in approximately $52,332,285 in the overseas box office giving it a worldwide total gross of $115,407,296.<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n\nThe 2010 remake's opening weekend put it ahead of the box office grosses for ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge]]'' ($29,999,213), ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' ($25,504,513), ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child]]'' ($22,168,359), and ''[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare]]'' ($18,090,181).<ref name=\"Nightcomp\" /> <!-- When adjusting the opening weekend for the 1984 original for 2010 inflation, the remake out grossed Wes Craven's film $32,902,299 to $2,736,653.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.halfhill.com/inflation1.html|title=Tom's Inflation Calculator|publisher=Half Hill|accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref>--> When breaking the inflation-adjusted grosses down by per theater capita, the 1984 film averaged $16,585 per cinema compared to the remake's $9,874.<ref>Simple Averaging (Total opening gross/Number of theaters). For ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' (1984), the adjusted inflation gross was used over the unadjusted amount.</ref> Comparing the film to other Platinum Dunes remakes, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' is second in opening-weekend gross behind ''Friday the 13th'' with $40,570,365.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fridaythe13th09.htm |title=''Friday the 13th'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216104549/http://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fridaythe13th09.htm |archive-date=December 16, 2009 }}</ref> The film sits ahead of the other Platinum Dunes remakes, which includes ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (2003 film)|The Texas Chainsaw Massacre]]'' ($28,094,014),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tcm03.htm |title=''The Texas Chainsaw Massacre'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090116/https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tcm03.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> ''[[The Amityville Horror (2005 film)|The Amityville Horror]]'' ($23,507,007),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=amityvillehorror05.htm |title=''The Amityville Horror'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090157/https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=amityvillehorror05.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> and ''[[The Hitcher (2007 film)|The Hitcher]]'' ($7,818,239).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hitcher07.htm |title=''The Hitcher'' box office |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090202/https://secure.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hitcher07.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> As of 2018, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' is number nineteen on the list of top opening weekends for the month of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=04&p=.htm|title=Top Opening Weekends By Month|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=May 2, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100504135210/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=04&p=.htm| archive-date= May 4, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the remake is ninth in slasher films and eighth in horror remakes for all-time-highest-grossing films (unadjusted dollars).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=slasher.htm|title=Horror \u2013 Slasher: 1970 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100523000829/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=slasher.htm| archive-date= May 23, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=horrorremake.htm|title=Horror Remakes: 1982 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527153753/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=horrorremake.htm| archive-date= May 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> When comparing its opening weekends to other slasher films and horror remakes, ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' sits in fifth spots for both categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=slasher.htm&p=.htm|title=Horror \u2013 Slasher Opening Weekend: 1982 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100524023816/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=slasher.htm&p=.htm| archive-date= May 24, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=horrorremake.htm&p=.htm|title=Horror Remakes Opening Weekend: 1982 to present|publisher=IMDb|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=May 18, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100506194807/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?view=openings&id=horrorremake.htm&p=.htm| archive-date= May 6, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The 2010 remake was the second-highest-grossing film in the franchise in North America, just behind ''[[Freddy vs. Jason]]'' (unadjusted dollars) but number one worldwide.<ref name=\"Nightcomp\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' has an approval rating of 15% based on 178 reviews, with an average rating of 3.75/10.<ref name=\"tomatoes\" /> The site's critics consensus reads, \"Visually faithful but lacking the depth and subversive twists that made the original so memorable, the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' remake lives up to its title in the worst possible way.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/nightmare_on_elm_street_2010/ |title= A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010) |publisher= [[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006154017/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/nightmare_on_elm_street_2010/ |archive-date=October 6, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 35 out of 100 based on 25 reviews.<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/a-nightmare-on-elm-street|title=''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' (2010): Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=CNET Networks|accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] polls reported that the average grade cinemagoers gave the film was a \"C+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nicole Sperling|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/02/nightmare-box-office-furry-vengeance/|title=Box Office:'Nightmare' scares up $32 million; 'Furry Vengeance' can't cross $7 million|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=May 2, 2010|accessdate=May 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504214423/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/05/02/nightmare-box-office-furry-vengeance/|archive-date=May 4, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Their exit polls showed that audiences were evenly divided between males and females with 40% between 18 and 24 years of age and 20% under 18.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brandon Gray|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2751&p=.htm|title='Nightmare' Wakes Up in Top Spot|publisher=Internet Movie Database|work=Box Office Mojo|date=May 2, 2010|accessdate=May 3, 2010| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100504230500/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2751&p=.htm| archive-date= May 4, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a B\u2013 and concluded that, \"I did jump a few times, and I liked Haley's dour malevolence, but overall, the new ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' is a by-the-numbers bad dream that plays a little too much like a corporately ordered rerun. One, two, Freddy's coming for you. Three, four, we've been there before.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20365198,00.html|title=A Nightmare On Elm Street|author-link= Owen Gleiberman| last= Gleiberman |first= Owen|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=April 29, 2010|accessdate=April 29, 2010}}</ref> Michael Rechtshaffen of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' criticized the acting as \"lethargically lifeless\" and criticized Haley's portrayal of Krueger saying, \"Even with his electronically deepened voice and a pointless amount of backstory, there's just no replacing Englund.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/a-nightmare-elm-street-film-29537|title=A Nightmare on Elm Street \u2013 Film Review|last=Rechtshaffen|first=Michael|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]] |date=October 14, 2010|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film one star out of four because he \"stared at ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' with weary resignation. The movie consists of a series of teenagers who are introduced, haunted by nightmares and then slashed to death by Freddy. So what? Are we supposed to be scared? Is the sudden clanging chord supposed to evoke a fearful [[Classical conditioning|Pavlovian]] response?\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/a-nightmare-on-elm-street-2010 |title=A Nightmare on Elm Street review|last= Ebert |first= Roger|author-link=Roger Ebert|work=Chicago Sun-Times|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]] |date= April 28, 2010|accessdate= May 5, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nOn January 5, 2011, the film won the [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award]] for best horror film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gossipcop.com/peoples-choice-awards-winners-fans-vote-favorite-2011/ |title=People's Choice Awards winners &#124; People's Choice Awards 2011 |publisher=Gossip Cop |date=January 5, 2011 |accessdate=July 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/658fneAgx?url=http://www.gossipcop.com/peoples-choice-awards-winners-fans-vote-favorite-2011/ |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010 film)}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.nightmareonelmstreet.com/}}\n* {{AllRovi title|430365|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n* {{Mojo title|nightmareonelmstreet10|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n* {{IMDb title|1179056|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n* [http://www.metacritic.com/movie/a-nightmare-on-elm-street/ ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''] at [[Metacritic]]\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|nightmare_on_elm_street_2010|A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n\n{{A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n{{Platinum Dunes}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nightmare On Elm Street}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010 horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s ghost films]]\n[[Category:2010s teen horror films]]\n[[Category:2010s slasher films]]\n[[Category:American film remakes]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American ghost films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:American teen horror films]]\n[[Category:American slasher films]]\n[[Category:A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:D-Box motion-enhanced films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Horror film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Platinum Dunes films]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael Bay]]\n[[Category:Films about child abuse]]\n[[Category:Films about 