{"title_page": "The Hunt (2012 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Hunt\n| image          = The Hunt (2012 film).jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Thomas Vinterberg]]\n| producer       = {{Plain list|\n* Morten Kaufmann\n* [[Sisse Graum J\u00f8rgensen]]\n* Thomas Vinterberg\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plain list|\n* [[Tobias Lindholm]]\n* Thomas Vinterberg\n}}\n| starring       = [[Mads Mikkelsen]]\n| music          = Nikolaj Egelund\n| cinematography = [[Charlotte Bruus Christensen]]\n| editing        = {{Plain list|\n* Anne \u00d8sterud\n* Janus Billeskov Jansen\n}}\n| studio         = [[Zentropa]]\n| distributor    = [[Nordisk Film]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2012|05|20|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2013|01|10|Denmark}}\n| runtime        = 115 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 115:27--><ref>{{cite web |title=Jagten - The Hunt |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/jagten-hunt-2012-0 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=28 August 2012 |accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = Denmark\n| language       = Danish<br> English\n| budget         = $3.45 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Jagten (2012) - Financial Information |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Jagten#tab=summary |publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $18.3 million<ref name=\"Numbers\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''The Hunt''''' ({{lang-da|'''Jagten'''}}) is a 2012 Danish [[drama film|drama]] film directed by [[Thomas Vinterberg]] and starring [[Mads Mikkelsen]]. The story is set in a small Danish village around Christmas, and follows a man who becomes the target of [[mass hysteria]] after being wrongly accused of sexually abusing a child in his kindergarten class.<ref name=\"tilcannes\" /><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/9711873/The-Hunt-review.html |title=''The Hunt'', review |accessdate=30 November 2012 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nThe film was screened at the [[2012 Toronto International Film Festival]] and competed at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]] where Mikkelsen won the [[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Actor Award]] for his role.<ref name=\"The Hunt\">{{cite web |url=http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2012/hunt |title=The Hunt |accessdate=10 December 2012 | work=TIFF}}</ref><ref name=\"Official Selection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/58878.html |title=2012 Official Selection |accessdate=25 April 2012 |work=Cannes}}</ref><ref name=\"timeout\">{{cite web |url=http://www.timeout.com/london/feature/2547/cannes-film-festival-2012-line-up-announced |title=Cannes Film Festival 2012 line-up announced |accessdate=25 April 2012 |work=timeout}}</ref> It also won the 2013 [[Nordic Council Film Prize]]. The film was selected as the Danish entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[86th Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"Denmark\">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/09/denmark-selects-the-hunt-as-foreign-language-oscar-candidate/ |title=Denmark Selects 'The Hunt' As Foreign Language Oscar Candidate |accessdate=26 September 2013 |work=Deadline}}</ref><ref name=\"HWR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-denmark-nominates-hunt-best-637329 |title=Oscars: Denmark Nominates 'The Hunt' for Best Foreign Language Category |accessdate=26 September 2013 |work=Hollywood Report}}</ref> making the final nomination.<ref name=\"Oscar Nom\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25757345 |title=Oscars: Main nominations 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> It was nominated in the same category at the [[71st Golden Globe Awards|2013 Golden Globe Awards]].<ref name=GGnom/>\n\n==Plot==\nAfter budget cuts cost him his job as a high school teacher, Lucas takes a job as a preschool teacher in the close-knit Danish community where he grew up. He is divorced and struggles to maintain a relationship with his teenage son, Marcus. Marcus lives with Lucas' ex-wife, but he eventually decides to move in with Lucas. Nadja, a Russian emigrant and another teacher at the preschool, makes advances on Lucas and eventually becomes his girlfriend.\n\nOne of Lucas' students is a five-year-old girl named Klara, the daughter of his best friend, Theo. She has an [[Puppy love|innocent crush]] on Lucas, who treats her kindly, whereas her parents constantly argue; he also lets her walk his dog, Fanny. One day, Klara puts a heart-shaped ornament into his coat pocket, then gives him a kiss on the lips. After Lucas admonishes her, Klara's feelings are hurt. Drawing on a memory of a pornographic photo her older teenage brother and his friend showed her, she makes comments describing an erect penis; this leads Grethe, the preschool director, to believe Lucas [[indecent exposure|exposed]] himself to Klara. Grethe brings in a psychologist who asks Klara [[leading questions]] about what occurred; Klara gives unclear responses about Lucas, alternately denying and confirming the abuse.\n\nGrethe doesn't believe that a child would lie about such a serious matter. She informs the other parents that Klara was likely abused; she also advises them to look for signs of sexual abuse in their own children. The parents ask leading questions of their children, who also say they were abused, thereby destroying any public doubt about Klara's story. Lucas is fired, and the community quickly shuns him, labeling him as a [[Paedophilia|paedophile]].\n\nLucas tries to get some answers out of Grethe, but she is still convinced that the children are telling the truth. Johan, one of Lucas' drinking buddies, leads Lucas away and orders him to go home.\n\nLucas shows up to Theo's house and suggests that the two of them discuss the issue with Grethe before things get worse. However, Theo insists that his daughter has never once lied, and he says he isn't sure whom to believe. Theo's wife, Agnes, on the other hand, is certain that Lucas is guilty; she becomes enraged and throws him out, refusing to listen to his protests. As Lucas is leaving, Theo grabs him, pins him against the wall, and threatens to kill him if the accusations turn out to be true. After Lucas has left, Klara tries to tell her mother that he didn't do anything, but Agnes merely believes that Klara is in denial.\n\nLucas' friendship with Theo is subsequently destroyed. His relationship with Nadja is likewise ruined when she expresses uncertainty at his innocence, causing him to angrily throw her out of the house. Marcus, who arrives to move in with Lucas, becomes [[Ostracism|ostracised]] by association, and he is told by a grocery employee that neither he nor his father are welcome to shop there anymore. Lucas survives only with the financial support of his close friend Bruun\u2014whose father is extremely wealthy\u2014and of a few friends who still believe him.\n\nLucas is arrested on suspicion of sexual assault. However, the children's accounts all involve Lucas abusing them in his basement, which supports Lucas' innocence as his house has no basement. After a hearing, Lucas is released without charge, and he celebrates with Marcus and Bruun.\n\nDespite the ruling, the community still believes Lucas is guilty, and the ostracism turns into violence. Lucas' dog is killed, and a large stone is thrown through his kitchen window. Marcus decides to take matters into his own hands and visits Theo, who lets him enter his house as Marcus is friends with Klara's teenage brother. In front of the other half of Lucas' and Theo's group of friends, who have sided with Theo, Marcus accuses Klara of lying and spits at her, and is promptly attacked. He is only spared serious injury by Theo, who intervenes and tells Marcus to leave. Deciding that the situation is too dangerous, Lucas sends Marcus away to live with his mother. Without his son as an in-between, Lucas is forced to go grocery shopping himself, and when a butcher at the grocery store viciously assaults him, Lucas retaliates by breaking his nose.\n\nOn Christmas Eve, Lucas reaches his breaking point; he angrily confronts, then beats Theo in front of everyone during a church service, telling him and the rest of the town to leave him alone. That night, Klara, mistaking her father for Lucas, apologizes to him as she drifts off to sleep. She insists that she didn't want things to turn out this way and that Lucas did nothing wrong. Realizing Lucas' innocence, Theo later visits him with food and alcohol as a peace offering.\n\nA year later, tensions in the community have simmered down, and everyone seems to have welcomed Lucas back in. Lucas and Nadja rekindle their relationship, and Marcus is accepted into the local hunting society as an adult. On a hunting expedition to commemorate the event, someone apparently shoots at Lucas with a rifle and barely misses. Blinded by the setting sun, Lucas is unable to identify his attacker. A moment later the unknown shooter flees in to the forest.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mads Mikkelsen]] as Lucas\n* [[Alexandra Rapaport]] as Nadja, Lucas' girlfriend\n* [[Thomas Bo Larsen]] as Theo, Lucas' best friend\n* Lasse Fogelstr\u00f8m as Marcus, Lucas' son\n* [[Susse Wold]] as Grethe\n* [[Lars Ranthe]] as Bruun\n* [[Anne Louise Hassing]] as Agnes, Theo's wife\n* [[Bjarne Henriksen]] as Ole\n* Annika Wedderkopp as Klara, Theo and Agnes' daughter\n* Ole Dupont as Landowner / Lawyer\n\n==Production==\nThe film was produced by [[Zentropa]] for 20 million [[Danish krone]]r. It received co-production support from Sweden's [[Film i V\u00e4st]] and Zentropa International Sweden. Further support came from the [[Danish Film Institute]], [[DR (broadcaster)|DR]], [[Eurimages]], Nordisk Film & TV Fond, the [[Swedish Film Institute]], [[Sveriges Television]] and the [[MEDIA Programme]].<ref name=\"tilcannes\">{{Cite web|author=Staff writer|date=19 April 2012|url=http://www.dfi.dk/Nyheder/NyhederFraDFI/2012/Vinterberg-til-Cannes-Festival.aspx|title=Vinterberg til Cannes Festival|language=Danish|work=dfi.se|publisher=[[Danish Film Institute]]|accessdate=25 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711181050/http://www.dfi.dk/Nyheder/NyhederFraDFI/2012/Vinterberg-til-Cannes-Festival.aspx|archivedate=11 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Alexandra Rapaport Thomas Vinterberg Cannes 2012.JPG|thumb|Alexandra Rapaport and Thomas Vinterberg at the 2012 Cannes Film Festival]]\n\n===Box office===\n''The Hunt'' [[Film premiere|premiered]] on 20 May 2012 at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]], as the first Danish-language film in the main competition since 1998.<ref name=\"tilcannes\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/assets/File/WEB%202012/horaires_proj/Horaire%202012_grand_2.pdf|title=Screenings guide|work=festival-cannes.fr|publisher=[[Cannes Film Festival]]|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> [[Mads Mikkelsen]] won the [[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Actor Award]] at Cannes.<ref name=\"PalmeDor2012\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/archives/2012/awardCompetition.html |title=Awards 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2012|work=Cannes}}</ref> Given its estimated $3.8 million budget, the film was a financial success; in total, it earned more than $16 million including $7.9 million in Denmark. In the United States, it was shown in 47 theaters and earned $613,308.<ref name=\"boxofficemojo.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hunt2013.htm|title=The Hunt (2013) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=hunt2013.htm|title=The Hunt (2013) - International Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received universal acclaim. It has an approval rating of 94% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 130 reviews, with an average rating of 7.9 out of 10. The website's critical consensus states: \"Anchored by Mads Mikkelsen's sympathetic performance, ''The Hunt'' asks difficult questions with the courage to pursue answers head on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_hunt_2013/|title=The Hunt (2013)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref> The film also has a score of 77 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]] based on 30 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-hunt|title=The Hunt Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Date of ceremony\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[86th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]\n| 2 March 2014\n| [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]<ref>{{cite news|title=2013 EDA Award Nominess|url=http://awfj.org/eda-awards/2013-eda-award-nominees/|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]|date=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n| 19 December 2013\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[66th British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Awards]]\n| 10 February 2013\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Film not in the English Language]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[British Independent Film Awards 2012|British Independent Film Awards]]\n| 9 December 2012\n| [[BIFA Award for Best Foreign Independent Film|Best Foreign Independent Film]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| [[67th Bodil Awards|Bodil Awards]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bodilprisen.dk/|title=2014 Bodil Awards Nominations|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"7\"| 1 February 2014\n| [[Bodil Award for Best Danish Film|Best Danish Film]]\n| \n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Bodil Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Mads Mikkelsen]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Best Supporting Actor\n| [[Thomas Bo Larsen]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[Lars Ranthe]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Best Supporting Actress\n| [[Anne Louise Hassing]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[Susse Wold]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Charlotte Bruus Christensen\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 27 May 2012\n| [[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Actor]]\n| Mads Mikkelsen\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Prize of the Ecumenical Jury]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Vulcan Award]]\n| Charlotte Bruus Christensen\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Palme d'Or]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards 2013|Chicago Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| 16 December 2013\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[19th Critics' Choice Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]]\n| 16 January 2014\n| [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association Awards 2013|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association]]\n| 16 December 2013\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[18th Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n| 23 February 2014\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[25th European Film Awards|European Film Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 1 December 2012\n| [[European Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Mads Mikkelsen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Screenwriter|Best Screenwriter]]\n|  Thomas Vinterberg, Tobias Lindholm\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Editor|Best Editor]]\n| Janus Billeskov Jansen, Anne \u00d8sterud\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[71st Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]<ref name=GGnom>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/awards/2014-golden-globes-nominee-list-1200948220/|title=Golden Globes Nominations: The Full List|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=11 January 2014|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref>\n| 12 January 2014\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| \n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[29th Independent Spirit Awards|Independent Spirit Awards]]\n| 1 March 2014\n| [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Foreign Film|Best Foreign Film]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[International Online Film Critics' Poll]]\n| 26 January 2015\n| Best Actor\n| Mads Mikkelsen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[London Film Critics Circle Awards 2012|London Film Critics Circle Awards]]\n| 20 January 2013\n| [[London Film Critics Circle Award for Actor of the Year|Actor of the Year]]\n| Mads Mikkelsen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Board of Review Awards 2013|National Board of Review Awards]]\n| 4 December 2013\n| Top Foreign Films\n| \n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Nordic Council Film Prize]]\n| 30 October 2013\n| Nordic Council Film Prize\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Online Film Critics Society Awards 2013|Online Film Critics Society Awards]]\n| 16 December 2013\n| [[Online Film Critics Society Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Mads Mikkelsen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"15\"| [[Robert Award]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/the-hunt-sweeps-danish-robert-awards/5065834.article|title=The Hunt sweeps Danish Robert awards|accessdate=31 January 2014|date=27 January 2014}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"15\"| 27 January 2014\n| [[Robert Award for Best Danish Film|Best Danish Film]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Robert Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Screenplay\n| Thomas Vinterberg,Tobias Lindholm\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Robert Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]]\n| Mads Mikkelsen\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| Thomas Bo Larsen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Best Supporting Actress\n| Susse Wold\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Anne Louise Hassing\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Charlotte Bruus Christensen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Editor\n| Anne \u00d8sterud, Janus Billeskov Jansen\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Production Design\n| Torben Stig Nielsen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Costume Design\n| Manon Rasmussen\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Make-Up\n| Bj\u00f8rg Serup\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Original Score\n| Nikolaj Egelund\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Sound\n| Kristian Eidnes Andersen, Thomas J\u00e6ger\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Audience Award - Best Drama\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Awards 2013|St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| 16 December 2013\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society|San Diego Film Critics Society Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdfcs.org/san-diego-film-critics-select-top-films-for-2013/|title=San Diego Film Critics Select Top Films for 2013|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref>\n| 11 December 2013\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Toronto Film Critics Association Awards|Toronto Film Critics Association]]<ref>{{cite news|title=TFCA Announces 2013 Awards|url=http://www.torontofilmcritics.com/|accessdate=22 December 2013|newspaper=Toronto Film Critics Association|date=16 December 2013}}</ref>\n| 16 December 2013\n| [[Toronto Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| \n| {{won|Runner-up}}\n|-\n| [[Vancouver International Film Festival]]\n| 12 October 2012\n| Rogers People's Choice Award\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2013|Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| 9 December 2013\n| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Home media==\n[[Nordisk Film]] released it in Denmark on 10 January 2013.<ref name=\"tilcannes\" /> The film was released on DVD and Blu-ray on 7 May 2013.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 86th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Danish submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[False allegation of child sexual abuse]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.magpictures.com/thehunt/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2106476|The Hunt}}\n* {{mojo title|hunt2013|The Hunt}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_hunt_2013|The Hunt}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-hunt|The Hunt}}\n* {{DNFt|74245}}\n\n{{Thomas Vinterberg}}\n{{The Nordic Council Film Prize}}\n{{Bodil Award for Best Danish Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunt, The}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:Danish-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s independent films]]\n[[Category:Danish films]]\n[[Category:Danish drama films]]\n[[Category:Danish independent films]]\n[[Category:Films about bullying]]\n[[Category:Films about educators]]\n[[Category:Films about pedophilia]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Thomas Vinterberg]]\n[[Category:Films set in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Tobias Lindholm]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2012 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Hunt\n| image          = The Hunt (2012 film).jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Thomas Vinterberg]]\n| producer       = {{Plain list|\n* Morten Kaufmann\n* [[Sisse Graum J\u00f8rgensen]]\n* Thomas Vinterberg\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plain list|\n* [[Tobias Lindholm]]\n* Thomas Vinterberg\n}}\n| starring       = [[Mads Mikkelsen]]\n| music          = Nikolaj Egelund\n| cinematography = [[Charlotte Bruus Christensen]]\n| editing        = {{Plain list|\n* Anne \u00d8sterud\n* Janus Billeskov Jansen\n}}\n| studio         = [[Zentropa]]\n| distributor    = [[Nordisk Film]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2012|05|20|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2013|01|10|Denmark}}\n| runtime        = 115 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 115:27--><ref>{{cite web |title=Jagten - The Hunt |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/jagten-hunt-2012-0 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=28 August 2012 |accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = Denmark\n| language       = Danish<br> English\n| budget         = $3.45 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Jagten (2012) - Financial Information |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Jagten#tab=summary |publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $18.3 million<ref name=\"Numbers\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''The Hunt''''' ({{lang-da|'''Jagten'''}}) is a 2012 Danish [[drama film|drama]] film directed by [[Thomas Vinterberg]] and starring [[Mads Mikkelsen]]. The story is set in a small Danish village around Christmas, and follows a man who becomes the target of [[mass hysteria]] after being wrongly accused of sexually abusing a child in his kindergarten class.<ref name=\"tilcannes\" /><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/9711873/The-Hunt-review.html |title=''The Hunt'', review |accessdate=30 November 2012 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nThe film was screened at the [[2012 Toronto International Film Festival]] and competed at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]] where Mikkelsen won the [[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Actor Award]] for his role.<ref name=\"The Hunt\">{{cite web |url=http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2012/hunt |title=The Hunt |accessdate=10 December 2012 | work=TIFF}}</ref><ref name=\"Official Selection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/58878.html |title=2012 Official Selection |accessdate=25 April 2012 |work=Cannes}}</ref><ref name=\"timeout\">{{cite web |url=http://www.timeout.com/london/feature/2547/cannes-film-festival-2012-line-up-announced |title=Cannes Film Festival 2012 line-up announced |accessdate=25 April 2012 |work=timeout}}</ref> It also won the 2013 [[Nordic Council Film Prize]]. The film was selected as the Danish entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[86th Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"Denmark\">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/09/denmark-selects-the-hunt-as-foreign-language-oscar-candidate/ |title=Denmark Selects 'The Hunt' As Foreign Language Oscar Candidate |accessdate=26 September 2013 |work=Deadline}}</ref><ref name=\"HWR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-denmark-nominates-hunt-best-637329 |title=Oscars: Denmark Nominates 'The Hunt' for Best Foreign Language Category |accessdate=26 September 2013 |work=Hollywood Report}}</ref> making the final nomination.<ref name=\"Oscar Nom\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25757345 |title=Oscars: Main nominations 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> It was nominated in the same category at the [[71st Golden Globe Awards|2013 Golden Globe Awards]].<ref name=GGnom/>\n\n==Plot==\nAfter budget cuts cost him his job as a high school teacher, Lucas takes a job as a preschool teacher in the close-knit Danish community where he grew up. He is divorced and struggles to maintain a relationship with his teenage son, Marcus. Marcus lives with Lucas' ex-wife, but he eventually decides to move in with Lucas. Nadja, a Russian emigrant and another teacher at the preschool, makes advances on Lucas and eventually becomes his girlfriend.\n\nOne of Lucas' students is a five-year-old girl named Klara, the daughter of his best friend, Theo. She has an [[Puppy love|innocent crush]] on Lucas, who treats her kindly, whereas her parents constantly argue; he also lets her walk his dog, Fanny. One day, Klara puts a heart-shaped ornament into his coat pocket, then gives him a kiss on the lips. After Lucas admonishes her, Klara's feelings are hurt. Drawing on a memory of a pornographic photo her older teenage brother and his friend showed her, she makes comments describing an erect penis; this leads Grethe, the preschool director, to believe Lucas [[indecent exposure|exposed]] himself to Klara. Grethe brings in a psychologist who asks Klara [[leading questions]] about what occurred; Klara gives unclear responses about Lucas, alternately denying and confirming the abuse.\n\nGrethe doesn't believe that a child would lie about such a serious matter. She informs the other parents that Klara was likely abused; she also advises them to look for signs of sexual abuse in their own children. The parents ask leading questions of their children, who also say they were abused, thereby destroying any public doubt about Klara's story. Lucas is fired, and the community quickly shuns him, labeling him as a [[Paedophilia|paedophile]].\n\nLucas tries to get some answers out of Grethe, but she is still convinced that the children are telling the truth. Johan, one of Lucas' drinking buddies, leads Lucas away and orders him to go home.\n\nLucas shows up to Theo's house and suggests that the two of them discuss the issue with Grethe before things get worse. However, Theo insists that his daughter has never once lied, and he says he isn't sure whom to believe. Theo's wife, Agnes, on the other hand, is certain that Lucas is guilty; she becomes enraged and throws him out, refusing to listen to his protests. As Lucas is leaving, Theo grabs him, pins him against the wall, and threatens to kill him if the accusations turn out to be true. After Lucas has left, Klara tries to tell her mother that he didn't do anything, but Agnes merely believes that Klara is in denial.\n\nLucas' friendship with Theo is subsequently destroyed. His relationship with Nadja is likewise ruined when she expresses uncertainty at his innocence, causing him to angrily throw her out of the house. Marcus, who arrives to move in with Lucas, becomes [[Ostracism|ostracised]] by association, and he is told by a grocery employee that neither he nor his father are welcome to shop there anymore. Lucas survives only with the financial support of his close friend Bruun\u2014whose father is extremely wealthy\u2014and of a few friends who still believe him.\n\nLucas is arrested on suspicion of sexual assault. However, the children's accounts all involve Lucas abusing them in his basement, which supports Lucas' innocence as his house has no basement. After a hearing, Lucas is released without charge, and he celebrates with Marcus and Bruun.\n\nDespite the ruling, the community still believes Lucas is guilty, and the ostracism turns into violence. Lucas' dog is killed, and a large stone is thrown through his kitchen window. Marcus decides to take matters into his own hands and visits Theo, who lets him enter his house as Marcus is friends with Klara's teenage brother. In front of the other half of Lucas' and Theo's group of friends, who have sided with Theo, Marcus accuses Klara of lying and spits at her, and is promptly attacked. He is only spared serious injury by Theo, who intervenes and tells Marcus to leave. Deciding that the situation is too dangerous, Lucas sends Marcus away to live with his mother. Without his son as an in-between, Lucas is forced to go grocery shopping himself, and when a butcher at the grocery store viciously assaults him, Lucas retaliates by breaking his nose.\n\nOn Christmas Eve, Lucas reaches his breaking point; he angrily confronts, then beats Theo in front of everyone during a church service, telling him and the rest of the town to leave him alone. That night, Klara, mistaking her father for Lucas, apologizes to him as she drifts off to sleep. She insists that she didn't want things to turn out this way and that Lucas did nothing wrong. Realizing Lucas' innocence, Theo later visits him with food and alcohol as a peace offering.\n\nA year later, tensions in the community have simmered down, and everyone seems to have welcomed Lucas back in. Lucas and Nadja rekindle their relationship, and Marcus is accepted into the local hunting society as an adult. On a hunting expedition to commemorate the event, someone apparently shoots at Lucas with a rifle and barely misses. Blinded by the setting sun, Lucas is unable to identify his attacker. A moment later the unknown shooter flees in to the forest.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mads Mikkelsen]] as Lucas\n* [[Alexandra Rapaport]] as Nadja, Lucas' girlfriend\n* [[Thomas Bo Larsen]] as Theo, Lucas' best friend\n* Lasse Fogelstr\u00f8m as Marcus, Lucas' son\n* [[Susse Wold]] as Grethe\n* [[Lars Ranthe]] as Bruun\n* [[Anne Louise Hassing]] as Agnes, Theo's wife\n* [[Bjarne Henriksen]] as Ole\n* Annika Wedderkopp as Klara, Theo and Agnes' daughter\n* Ole Dupont as Landowner / Lawyer\n\n==Production==\nThe film was produced by [[Zentropa]] for 20 million [[Danish krone]]r. It received co-production support from Sweden's [[Film i V\u00e4st]] and Zentropa International Sweden. Further support came from the [[Danish Film Institute]], [[DR (broadcaster)|DR]], [[Eurimages]], Nordisk Film & TV Fond, the [[Swedish Film Institute]], [[Sveriges Television]] and the [[MEDIA Programme]].<ref name=\"tilcannes\">{{Cite web|author=Staff writer|date=19 April 2012|url=http://www.dfi.dk/Nyheder/NyhederFraDFI/2012/Vinterberg-til-Cannes-Festival.aspx|title=Vinterberg til Cannes Festival|language=Danish|work=dfi.se|publisher=[[Danish Film Institute]]|accessdate=25 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711181050/http://www.dfi.dk/Nyheder/NyhederFraDFI/2012/Vinterberg-til-Cannes-Festival.aspx|archivedate=11 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Alexandra Rapaport Thomas Vinterberg Cannes 2012.JPG|thumb|Alexandra Rapaport and Thomas Vinterberg at the 2012 Cannes Film Festival]]\n\n===Box office===\n''The Hunt'' [[Film premiere|premiered]] on 20 May 2012 at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]], as the first Danish-language film in the main competition since 1998.<ref name=\"tilcannes\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/assets/File/WEB%202012/horaires_proj/Horaire%202012_grand_2.pdf|title=Screenings guide|work=festival-cannes.fr|publisher=[[Cannes Film Festival]]|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> [[Mads Mikkelsen]] won the [[Best Actor Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Actor Award]] at Cannes.<ref name=\"PalmeDor2012\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/archives/2012/awardCompetition.html |title=Awards 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2012|work=Cannes}}</ref> Given its estimated $3.8 million budget, the film was a financial success; in total, it earned more than $16 million including $7.9 million in Denmark. In the United States, it was shown in 47 theaters and earned $613,308.<ref name=\"boxofficemojo.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hunt2013.htm|title=The Hunt (2013) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=hunt2013.htm|title=The Hunt (2013) - International Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received universal acclaim. It has an approval rating of 94% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 130 reviews, with an average rating of 7.9 out of 10. The website's critical consensus states: \"Anchored by Mads Mikkelsen's sympathetic performance, ''The Hunt'' asks difficult questions with the courage to pursue answers head on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_hunt_2013/|title=The Hunt (2013)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref> The film also has a score of 77 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]] based on 30 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-hunt|title=The Hunt Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Date of ceremony\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[86th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]\n| 2 March 2014\n| [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]<ref>{{cite news|title=2013 EDA Award Nominess|url=http://awfj.org/eda-awards/2013-eda-award-nominees/|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]|date=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n| 19 December 2013\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[66th British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Awards]]\n| 10 February 2013\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Film not in the English Language]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[British Independent Film Awards 2012|British Independent Film Awards]]\n| 9 December 2012\n| [[BIFA Award for Best Foreign Independent Film|Best Foreign Independent Film]]\n| Thomas Vinterberg\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| [[67th Bodil Awards|Bodil Awards]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bodilprisen.dk/|title=2014 Bodil Awards Nominations|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"7\"| 1 February 2014\n| [[Bodil Award for Best Danish Film|Best D