{"title_page": "Soyuz MS-14", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Soyuz MS-14\n| image                 = Soyuz MS-14 approaches the ISS (first attempt).jpg\n| image_caption         = The Soyuz MS-14 approaches the ISS (first attempt).\n| insignia              = Soyuz-MS-14-Mission-Patch.png\n\n| mission_type          = Test flight\n| operator              = [[Roscosmos]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = \n| SATCAT                = \n| mission_duration      = {{time interval|2019-08-22, 03:38|2019-09-06, 21:23|show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n| distance_travelled    = \n| orbits_completed      = \n\n| spacecraft            = \n| spacecraft_type       = [[Soyuz-MS]] 11F747\n| manufacturer          = [[RKK Energia]]\n| launch_mass           = \n| landing_mass          = \n\n| launch_date           = {{start date|2019|08|22|03|38||Z|df=yes}} <ref name=rc-2019-plan>{{cite news|url=https://www.roscosmos.ru/26107/|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0443\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u041c\u041a\u0421 \u043d\u0430 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434|language=ru|trans-title=Federal commission approved plan of ISS launches in 2019 |publisher=[[Roscosmos]]|date=26 February 2019 |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=Space.com>https://www.space.com/russia-launches-humanoid-robot-on-soyuz-spacecraft.html</ref>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Soyuz-2.1a]]\n| launch_site           = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Pad 31/6]]\n\n| landing_date          = {{end date|2019|09|06|21|32||Z|df=yes}} <ref name=\"Land\">[https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/09/06/soyuz-spacecraft-humanoid-robot-return-to-earth-after-16-day-test-flight/ Soyuz spacecraft, humanoid robot return to Earth after 16-day test flight]</ref>\n| landing_site          = 147 km southeast of [[Jezkazgan|Dzheskasgan]]<ref name=SF/>\n\n| orbit_epoch           = \n| orbit_reference       = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis       = \n| orbit_apoapsis        = \n| orbit_inclination     = 51.6\u00b0\n| orbit_period          = \n| apsis                 = gee\n\n| docking               = \n {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]<br>(First attempt)\n   | docking_type       = dock\n   | docking_port       = ''[[Poisk (ISS module)|Poisk]]'' zenith\n   | docking_date       = Aborted: 24 August 2019, 05:36 [[UTC]] <ref name=SF>[http://www.spacefacts.de/iss/english/exp_60.htm Expedition 60]</ref>\n   | undocking_date     = \n   | time_docked        = \n}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]<br>(Second attempt)\n   | docking_type       = dock\n   | docking_port       = ''[[Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda]]'' aft\n   | docking_date       = 27 August 2019, 03:08 [[UTC]] <ref name=Dock2>[https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/08/26/russian-spacecraft-second-docking-attempt-successful/Russian Spacecraft Second Docking Attempt Successful]</ref>\u00b7<ref name=SF/>\n   | undocking_date     = 06 September 2019, 18:14 [[UTC]] <ref>[https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/09/06/soyuz-ms-14-mission-status-center-2/ Live coverage: Soyuz test flight set to conclude today]</ref>\u00b7<ref name=SF/>\n   | time_docked        = {{time interval|2019-08-27 03:08|2019-09-06 18:14|show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n}}\n\n| cargo_mass            = 660 kg <ref name=Space.com/>\u00b7<ref name=NASA>https:blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation</ref>\n\n| previous_mission      = [[Soyuz MS-13]]\n| next_mission          = [[Soyuz MS-15]]\n| programme             = [[Soyuz programme]]\n}}\n'''Soyuz MS-14''' was a [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]] spaceflight to the [[International Space Station]].<ref name=rc-2019-plan /> It carried no crew members, as it was intended to test a modification of the [[Launch escape system|launch abort system]] for integration with the [[Soyuz-2.1a]] launch vehicle.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ria.ru/20181013/1530589596.html |title=\"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441\" \u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043f\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0434\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \"\u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437-2\" |lang=ru | trans-title=Roscosmos will test launch abort system before switching to Soyuz-2 |agency=[[RIA Novosti]] |date=13 October 2018 |access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> It launched successfully on 22 August 2019 at 03:38 [[UTC]].<ref name=Space.com/> It was the first mission of the Soyuz crew vehicle without a crew in 33 years, and the first ever unpiloted mission of Soyuz to ISS.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/soyuz-ms-14.html</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nUnlike the traditional [[Soyuz-FG]] launcher which is turned on its launchpad to set [[azimuth]] of its flight, Soyuz-2 performs a roll maneuver during its flight to change direction. The maneuver would trigger the analog launch abort system designed for Soyuz-FG. Soyuz MS-14 tested a solution for this issue. The 14th flight of Soyuz MS is the 143rd flight of a Soyuz spacecraft. If all goes well, future crewed missions will use the new configuration starting with [[Soyuz MS-16]] in early 2020.<ref name=ria-20181222>{{cite news |title=\u041e\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0443\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0441 \u0411\u0430\u0439\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0443\u0440\u0430 \u043a \u041c\u041a\u0421, \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a |trans-title=Launch dates to ISS from Baikonur are defined, per source |url=https://ria.ru/20181222/1548471154.html |accessdate=28 December 2018 |agency=[[RIA Novosti]] |date=22 December 2018 |language=ru}}</ref>\n\nBesides testing the integration of the new launcher and the abort system Soyuz MS-14 is also testing an upgraded navigation and propulsion control system.<ref name=energia-20180518>{{cite web |url=https://www.energia.ru/ru/news/news-2018/news_05-18.html |title=\u0420\u041a\u041a \u00ab\u042d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f\u00bb: \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442 \u0431\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u00ab\u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437\u0430 \u041c\u0421\u00bb \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0435 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 |lang=ru |trans-title=RKK Energia: launch of unmanned Soyuz MS is planned for August 2019 |publisher=[[RKK Energia]] |date=18 May 2018 |access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> The results of the testing will be used in the design of [[Soyuz GVK]], an uncrewed cargo delivery and return spacecraft, tentatively scheduled to be launched for the first time in 2022.<ref name=energia-20180518/>\n\nUnlike preceding and future Soyuz MS spacecraft, Soyuz MS-14 lacks various crew support systems.\n\nThe spacecraft carried cargo to the International Space Station, among other things a humanoid robot [[FEDOR (robot)|Fedor]] that travelled in the crew compartment of the Soyuz (which was available to use as the mission had no crew). The Fedor robot returned to Earth on 6 September 2019 in the landing crew capsule of Soyuz MS-14 (which was again uncrewed). According to NASA, {{convert|1450|lb}} of cargo were delivered to ISS.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/soyuz-ms-14.html</ref>\n\nThe spacecraft delivered the [[JEM-EUSO|Mini-EUSO]] telescope to the ISS.<ref>http://jem-euso.roma2.infn.it/?page_id=818</ref>\n\n==Docking==\n=== First attempt ===\nFollowing a flawless two-day long free flight and rendezvous with the ISS, MS-14 was scheduled to dock with the station's [[Poisk (ISS module)|''Poisk'']] module at 05:30 UTC on 24 August 2019. During the final phases of the spacecraft's approach to the ISS, its [[Kurs (docking navigation system)|Kurs rendezvous system]] failed to lock onto the station and the spacecraft was not able to dock. [[Expedition 60]] commander [[Aleksey Ovchinin]] commanded MS-14 to abort its docking, after which the spacecraft backed away to a safe distance from the ISS.<ref name=abort>{{cite news |last1=Tariq |first1=Malik |title=Russian Soyuz Spacecraft Carrying Humanoid Robot Aborts Docking at Space Station |url=https://www.space.com/soyuz-aborts-space-station-docking-ms-14.html |work=Space.com |date=24 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas most unmanned Russian spacecraft flying to ISS also feature a [[TORU]] backup system enabling cosmonauts to take manual control of the spacecraft from the ISS, this system was not fitted to MS-14.<ref name=sfn20190824 /> The fault was located on the Kurs signal amplifier on ISS's ''Poisk'' docking module, and initial plans called for the cosmonauts to replace this amplifier ahead of a new docking attempt.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russian Spacecraft Docking Attempt No Earlier Than Monday \u2013 Space Station |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/08/24/russian-spacecraft-docking-attempt-no-earlier-than-monday/ |work=blogs.nasa.gov |date=24 August 2019}}</ref> It was subsequently decided that, on 26 August, the crew of [[Soyuz MS-13]] would relocate their spacecraft from the aft port on the ''[[Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda]]'' module to perform a manual docking at the faulty ''Poisk'' port, freeing up a port for MS-14 to dock using Kurs on 27 August 2019.<ref name=sfn20190824>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Stephen |title=Station crew to clear new port for second Soyuz docking attempt \u2013 Spaceflight Now |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/08/24/station-crew-to-clear-port-for-second-soyuz-docking-attempt/|date=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Second attempt ===\n{{Expand section|date=September 2019}}\nThe MS-14 successfully docked at 03:08 [[UTC]] on 27 August 2019.<ref name=Dock2/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Soyuz}}\n{{Unmanned ISS flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Soyuz uncrewed test flights]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 in Russia]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Soyuz-2 rockets]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Soyuz MS-14\n| image                 = Soyuz MS-14 approaches the ISS (first attempt).jpg\n| image_caption         = The Soyuz MS-14 approaches the ISS (first attempt).\n| insignia              = Soyuz-MS-14-Mission-Patch.png\n\n| mission_type          = Test flight\n| operator              = [[Roscosmos]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = \n| SATCAT                = \n| mission_duration      = {{time interval|2019-08-22, 03:38|2019-09-06, 21:23|show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n| distance_travelled    = \n| orbits_completed      = \n\n| spacecraft            = \n| spacecraft_type       = [[Soyuz-MS]] 11F747\n| manufacturer          = [[RKK Energia]]\n| launch_mass           = \n| landing_mass          = \n\n| launch_date           = {{start date|2019|08|22|03|38||Z}} <ref name=rc-2019-plan>{{cite news|url=https://www.roscosmos.ru/26107/|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0443\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u041c\u041a\u0421 \u043d\u0430 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434|language=ru|trans-title=Federal commission approved plan of ISS launches in 2019 |publisher=[[Roscosmos]]|date=26 February 2019 |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=Space.com>https://www.space.com/russia-launches-humanoid-robot-on-soyuz-spacecraft.html</ref>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Soyuz-2.1a]]\n| launch_site           = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Pad 31/6]]\n\n| landing_date          = {{end date|2019|09|06|21|32||Z}} <ref name=\"Land\">[https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/09/06/soyuz-spacecraft-humanoid-robot-return-to-earth-after-16-day-test-flight/ Soyuz spacecraft, humanoid robot return to Earth after 16-day test flight]</ref>\n| landing_site          = 147 km southeast of [[Jezkazgan|Dzheskasgan]]<ref name=SF/>\n\n| orbit_epoch           = \n| orbit_reference       = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis       = \n| orbit_apoapsis        = \n| orbit_inclination     = 51.6\u00b0\n| orbit_period          = \n| apsis                 = gee\n\n| docking               = \n {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]<br>(First attempt)\n   | docking_type       = dock\n   | docking_port       = ''[[Poisk (ISS module)|Poisk]]'' zenith\n   | docking_date       = Aborted: 24 August 2019, 05:36 [[UTC]] <ref name=SF>[http://www.spacefacts.de/iss/english/exp_60.htm Expedition 60]</ref>\n   | undocking_date     = \n   | time_docked        = \n}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]<br>(Second attempt)\n   | docking_type       = dock\n   | docking_port       = ''[[Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda]]'' aft\n   | docking_date       = 27 August 2019, 03:08 [[UTC]] <ref name=Dock2>[https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/08/26/russian-spacecraft-second-docking-attempt-successful/Russian Spacecraft Second Docking Attempt Successful]</ref>\u00b7<ref name=SF/>\n   | undocking_date     = 06 September 2019, 18:14 [[UTC]] <ref>[https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/09/06/soyuz-ms-14-mission-status-center-2/ Live coverage: Soyuz test flight set to conclude today]</ref>\u00b7<ref name=SF/>\n   | time_docked        = {{time interval|2019-08-27 03:08|2019-09-06 18:14|show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n}}\n\n| cargo_mass            = 660 kg <ref name=Space.com/>\u00b7<ref name=NASA>https:blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation</ref>\n\n| previous_mission      = [[Soyuz MS-13]]\n| next_mission          = [[Soyuz MS-15]]\n| programme             = [[Soyuz programme]]\n}}\n'''Soyuz MS-14''' was a [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]] spaceflight to the [[International Space Station]].<ref name=rc-2019-plan /> It carried no crew members, as it was intended to test a modification of the [[Launch escape system|launch abort system]] for integration with the [[Soyuz-2.1a]] launch vehicle.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ria.ru/20181013/1530589596.html |title=\"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441\" \u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043f\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0434\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \"\u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437-2\" |lang=ru | trans-title=Roscosmos will test launch abort system before switching to Soyuz-2 |agency=[[RIA Novosti]] |date=13 October 2018 |access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> It launched successfully on 22 August 2019 at 03:38 [[UTC]].<ref name=Space.com/> It was the first mission of the Soyuz crew vehicle without a crew in 33 years, and the first ever unpiloted mission of Soyuz to ISS.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/soyuz-ms-14.html</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nUnlike the traditional [[Soyuz-FG]] launcher which is turned on its launchpad to set [[azimuth]] of its flight, Soyuz-2 performs a roll maneuver during its flight to change direction. The maneuver would trigger the analog launch abort system designed for Soyuz-FG. Soyuz MS-14 tested a solution for this issue. The 14th flight of Soyuz MS is the 143rd flight of a Soyuz spacecraft. If all goes well, future crewed missions will use the new configuration starting with [[Soyuz MS-16]] in early 2020.<ref name=ria-20181222>{{cite news |title=\u041e\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0443\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0441 \u0411\u0430\u0439\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0443\u0440\u0430 \u043a \u041c\u041a\u0421, \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a |trans-title=Launch dates to ISS from Baikonur are defined, per source |url=https://ria.ru/20181222/1548471154.html |accessdate=28 December 2018 |agency=[[RIA Novosti]] |date=22 December 2018 |language=ru}}</ref>\n\nBesides testing the integration of the new launcher and the abort system Soyuz MS-14 is also testing an upgraded navigation and propulsion control system.<ref name=energia-20180518>{{cite web |url=https://www.energia.ru/ru/news/news-2018/news_05-18.html |title=\u0420\u041a\u041a \u00ab\u042d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f\u00bb: \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442 \u0431\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u00ab\u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437\u0430 \u041c\u0421\u00bb \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0435 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 |lang=ru |trans-title=RKK Energia: launch of unmanned Soyuz MS is planned for August 2019 |publisher=[[RKK Energia]] |date=18 May 2018 |access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> The results of the testing will be used in the design of [[Soyuz GVK]], an uncrewed cargo delivery and return spacecraft, tentatively scheduled to be launched for the first time in 2022.<ref name=energia-20180518/>\n\nUnlike preceding and future Soyuz MS spacecraft, Soyuz MS-14 lacks various crew support systems.\n\nThe spacecraft carried cargo to the International Space Station, among other things a humanoid robot [[FEDOR (robot)|Fedor]] that travelled in the crew compartment of the Soyuz (which was available to use as the mission had no crew). The Fedor robot returned to Earth on 6 September 2019 in the landing crew capsule of Soyuz MS-14 (which was again uncrewed). According to NASA, {{convert|1450|lb}} of cargo were delivered to ISS.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/soyuz-ms-14.html</ref>\n\nThe spacecraft delivered the [[JEM-EUSO|Mini-EUSO]] telescope to the ISS.<ref>http://jem-euso.roma2.infn.it/?page_id=818</ref>\n\n==Docking==\n=== First attempt ===\nFollowing a flawless two-day long free flight and rendezvous with the ISS, MS-14 was scheduled to dock with the station's [[Poisk (ISS module)|''Poisk'']] module at 05:30 UTC on 24 August 2019. During the final phases of the spacecraft's approach to the ISS, its [[Kurs (docking navigation system)|Kurs rendezvous system]] failed to lock onto the station and the spacecraft was not able to dock. [[Expedition 60]] commander [[Aleksey Ovchinin]] commanded MS-14 to abort its docking, after which the spacecraft backed away to a safe distance from the ISS.<ref name=abort>{{cite news |last1=Tariq |first1=Malik |title=Russian Soyuz Spacecraft Carrying Humanoid Robot Aborts Docking at Space Station |url=https://www.space.com/soyuz-aborts-space-station-docking-ms-14.html |work=Space.com |date=24 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas most unmanned Russian spacecraft flying to ISS also feature a [[TORU]] backup system enabling cosmonauts to take manual control of the spacecraft from the ISS, this system was not fitted to MS-14.<ref name=sfn20190824 /> The fault was located on the Kurs signal amplifier on ISS's ''Poisk'' docking module, and initial plans called for the cosmonauts to replace this amplifier ahead of a new docking attempt.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russian Spacecraft Docking Attempt No Earlier Than Monday \u2013 Space Station |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/08/24/russian-spacecraft-docking-attempt-no-earlier-than-monday/ |work=blogs.nasa.gov |date=24 August 2019}}</ref> It was subsequently decided that, on 26 August, the crew of [[Soyuz MS-13]] would relocate their spacecraft from the aft port on the ''[[Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda]]'' module to perform a manual docking at the faulty ''Poisk'' port, freeing up a port for MS-14 to dock using Kurs on 27 August 2019.<ref name=sfn20190824>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Stephen |title=Station crew to clear new port for second Soyuz docking attempt \u2013 Spaceflight Now |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/08/24/station-crew-to-clear-port-for-second-soyuz-docking-attempt/|date=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Second attempt ===\n{{Expand section|date=September 2019}}\nThe MS-14 successfully docked at 03:08 [[UTC]] on 27 August 2019.<ref name=Dock2/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Soyuz}}\n{{Unmanned ISS flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Soyuz uncrewed test flights]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 in Russia]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Soyuz-2 rockets]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "Worldbruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "set df=yes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soyuz_MS-14"}
